page_table: {"pageid": 0, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@31_pendulums/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@31_pendulums-tab3", "text": "**Example 3.1** Model a lightly damped pendulum, consisting of a mass attached to a rod hanging from a pivot at the top.  **Parameters and functions:** Define  [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline]|  mass   ---|---   [mathjaxinline]l[/mathjaxinline]|  length of rod   [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] |  time   [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] |  angle measured counterclockwise from the rest position      Here [mathjaxinline]\\, m\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, l\\,[/mathjaxinline] are system parameters, [mathjaxinline]\\, t\\,[/mathjaxinline] is the independent variable, and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\theta \\,[/mathjaxinline] is a function of [mathjaxinline]\\, t.[/mathjaxinline]  **Simplifying assumptions:**    * The rod has negligible mass.     * The rod does not bend or stretch.     * The pivot is such that the motion is in a plane, so there is no Coriolis effect.     * The local gravitational field [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] is a constant, assuming the pendulum is not thousands of kilometers tall.   ![Pendulum hanging from a massless rod from a pivot point. The angle theta is measure to the right of vertical. The r theta coordinate has r pointing along the rod away from the pivot, and theta pointing tangent to the circle of motion to the right. The two forces acting on the pendulum are the tension, which points in the negative r direction, and the force due to gravity straight down. The component of gravity that points in the negative theta direction has magnitude sin theta times the magnitude of the force due to gravity.](/static/images/pendulum.svg)  **Equation:**  The motion of the mass is governed by Newton's second law  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\, m\\mathbf{a}=\\mathbf{F}.\\,[/mathjaxinline] | | (4.1)   ---|---|---|---      The net force [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{F}\\,[/mathjaxinline] consists of two components: the radial component, in the direction of [mathjaxinline]\\hat{r},\\,[/mathjaxinline] which is along the rod, and the tangential component, in the direction of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\hat{\\theta },\\,[/mathjaxinline] which is tangent to the arc traced out by the mass as it moves. At each position along the arc, these two components are perpendicular to one another.    The radial component of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{F}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is zero, since the rod is rigid and its tension cancels the radial component of the gravitational force regardless of the position of the mass.    The tangential component gives the differential equation determining the motion of the pendulum. Recall that arc length is the product of the radius and the sweeping angle. The pendulum has radius [mathjaxinline]l,\\,[/mathjaxinline] so the tangential component of the acceleration is [mathjaxinline]\\, l\\ddot{\\theta }.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] If the pendulum was frictionless, the net force in the tangential direction [mathjaxinline]\\hat{\\theta }\\,[/mathjaxinline] would be  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F_{\\hat{\\theta }}\\, =\\, m\\left(l \\ddot{\\theta }\\right)\\, =\\, - \\underset {{\\color{orange}{\\textrm{gravity}}} }{mg \\sin \\theta }.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.2)   ---|---|---|---      More realistically, the pendulum has friction, which can be assumed to be proportional to the tangential velocity [mathjaxinline]l\\dot{\\theta },\\,[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] as the constant of proportionality. Hence, the net force is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F_{\\hat{\\theta }}\\, =\\, m \\left(l \\ddot{\\theta }\\right) = - \\underset {{\\color{orange}{\\textrm{friction}}} }{b (l\\dot{\\theta })} - \\underset {{\\color{orange}{\\textrm{gravity}}} }{mg \\sin \\theta }.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.3)   ---|---|---|---      Dividing both sides by [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]l[/mathjaxinline] and rearranging, we have  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ddot{\\theta } +\\frac{b}{m}\\dot{\\theta } + \\frac{g}{l} \\sin \\theta[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.4)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      The first two terms, [mathjaxinline]\\ddot{\\theta }[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{b}{m} \\dot{\\theta },\\,[/mathjaxinline] are linear, but the third term [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\frac{g}{l} \\sin \\theta \\,[/mathjaxinline] is non-linear in [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] and makes this entire second order differential equation **non-linear**.    In the following discussion on the pendulum, we will assume its mass is [mathjaxinline]\\, m=1\\,[/mathjaxinline] and its length [mathjaxinline]\\, l=1\\,[/mathjaxinline] for simplicity (which is equivalent to measuring mass in units of [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline] and length in units of [mathjaxinline]l[/mathjaxinline]). The DE then reduces to  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ddot{\\theta } +b\\, \\dot{\\theta } + g \\sin \\theta[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0 \\qquad (b,g>0).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.5)   ---|---|---|---|---|---       **Remark 3.2** When [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] is small, it is reasonable to replace the non-linear term by its best linear approximation at [mathjaxinline]\\theta =0[/mathjaxinline], namely [mathjaxinline]\\sin \\theta \\approx \\theta .\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] This leads to  [mathjax]\\ddot{\\theta } + b\\, \\dot{\\theta } + g\\, \\theta = 0,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      the second order linear ODE for a damped oscillator with unit mass, damping constant [mathjaxinline]b,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and spring constant [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline]. This process is called **linearizing** the non-linear ODE.  Modeling", "filename": "31_pendulums-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Modeling"}

{"pageid": 1, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@15_stability/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@15_stability-tab8", "text": "Generalizing the preceding example, suppose a system has one zero and one nonzero eigenvalue, then its phase portrait is a **comb**.  **Comb** : Eigenvalues are **real and distinct** , with **exactly one being zero** .  Let [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _1=0,\\, \\lambda _2\\neq 0.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline].  Every point on the [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]-eigenline is **stationary**.      ---   Other trajectories are along lines **parallel to the eigenline corresponding to** [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{\\lambda _2\\neq 0},\\,[/mathjaxinline] and    * tending to infinity if [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _2>0[/mathjaxinline],     * approaching the [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] eigenline if [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _2<0[/mathjaxinline].   **General solution:** [mathjaxinline]c_1 \\mathbf v_1 + c_2 e^{\\lambda _2 t} \\mathbf v_2[/mathjaxinline]  | ![0-Eigenline of stationary points is depicted in blue. All other trajectories are parallel to the other eigenline and tend towards the 0-eigenline](/static/images/u3s4_comb.svg)      **On the trace-determinant plane:**    Combs are on the horizontal [mathjaxinline]\\, \\text{Tr}[/mathjaxinline]-axis except the origin on the [mathjaxinline](\\text{Tr},\\text{Det})[/mathjaxinline]-plane, since [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda _1=0\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda _2\\neq 0[/mathjaxinline] imply [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{\\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}= 0}} \\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathrm{tr}\\mathbf{A}\\neq 0[/mathjaxinline]. On the left half [mathjaxinline]\\text{Tr}[/mathjaxinline]-axis are attracting combs; the right are repelling combs.  ![Trace Determinant plane, attracting combs are the negative horizontal Tr axis \\(not including the origin\\), repelling combs are the positive horizontal Tr axis \\(not including the origin.](/static/images/u3s4_tdcomb.svg)  Combs", "filename": "15_stability-tab8-text1.html", "title": "Combs"}

{"pageid": 2, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab2", "text": "We will now discuss how to solve [mathjaxinline]2 \\times 2[/mathjaxinline] systems of DEs. In this course, we will consider only systems with constant coefficient matrices. We will also restrict ourselves to the homogeneous case. The method we learn can also be applied to solve larger ([mathjaxinline]n\\times n[/mathjaxinline]) systems, which we will discuss in the course _Linear algebra and systems of differential equations_. At that point, we will also consider the inhomogeneous case.  First, let us recall the notations we have used to present a first-order homogeneous [mathjaxinline]\\, 2 \\times 2 \\,[/mathjaxinline] system with constant coefficients. As a pair of coupled equations, the system is:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle ax+by[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.53)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle cx+dy\\qquad (a,\\, b,\\, c,\\, d \\, \\, \\, \\text{constant}).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.54)      In vector notation, the system is:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} \\dot x \\\\\\ \\dot y \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} a& b\\\\\\ c& d \\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} x\\\\\\ y \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.55)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      or more compactly,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}\\qquad \\,[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{where}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\, \\mathbf{x}= \\begin{pmatrix} x\\\\\\ y \\end{pmatrix},\\, \\, \\mathbf{A}= \\begin{pmatrix} a& b\\\\\\ c& d \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.56)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      The coefficient matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] is constant.    From now on in this course, when we refer to a system, we mean a **first order homogeneous** [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{2 \\times 2} \\,[/mathjaxinline] **system with constant coefficients**.    **How hard will solving such systems be?**   Recall that    * all second order linear differential equations can be written as first order linear [mathjaxinline]\\, 2\\times 2\\,[/mathjaxinline] systems using companion matrices;     * solving a second order linear ODE with constant coefficients involves solving a quadratic equation.   Therefore, the complete recipe for the solution to a first order [mathjaxinline]\\, 2\\times 2\\,[/mathjaxinline] system with constant coefficient must be at least as complicated as solving a quadratic equation. We will see that the full solution is expressed in terms of what are known as eigenvalues and eigenvectors of the coefficient matrix. For a [mathjaxinline]\\, 2\\times 2\\,[/mathjaxinline] system, the eigenvalues are the roots of a quadratic equation.  Introduction", "filename": "13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Introduction"}

[mathjaxinline](0,0),\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, (2\\pi ,0),\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, (4\\pi ,0),\\,[/mathjaxinline] and so on all correspond to the mass being at rest at the bottom.     2. [mathjaxinline](\\pi ,0),\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, (3\\pi ,0),\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, (5\\pi ,0),\\,[/mathjaxinline] and so on all correspond to the mass is being at the top, exactly above the pivot.   In the video below, we will discuss linearization at the critical point [mathjaxinline]\\, (\\pi ,0).\\,[/mathjaxinline] We will choose the system parameters to be [mathjaxinline]\\, b=1\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, g=2,\\,[/mathjaxinline] so the system is:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot{\\theta }[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\omega[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.55)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\omega }[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -\\omega - 2 \\sin \\theta .[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.56)  video note", "filename": "31_pendulums-tab10-text1.html", "title": "video note"}

{"pageid": 6, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@14_phaseportraits/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@14_phaseportraits-tab16", "text": "Now consider a damped oscillator described by [mathjaxinline]\\, m \\ddot{x} + {\\color{blue}{b \\dot{x}}} + k x = 0[/mathjaxinline]. The total energy and its time derivative are given by the same expression as before:  |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle E[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{m\\dot{x}^2}{2} + \\frac{kx^2}{2}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.65)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{E}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x} (m\\ddot{x} + kx).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.66)      But the differential equation now gives [mathjaxinline]\\, m\\ddot{x} + kx={\\color{blue}{-b\\dot{x}}} ,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and therefore  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot{E}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x} ({\\color{blue}{-b\\dot{x}}} )\\, =\\, -b \\dot{x}^2<0.[/mathjaxinline] | | (3.67)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      In other words, energy is lost from the mass due to friction. The dashpot heats up. This means the phase plane trajectory crosses through the equal- energy ellipses, inwards towards the origin.  It may spiral in (underdamped case), or approach the origin more directly (critically damped and overdamped cases).  ![See caption](/static/images/u3s3_energyspiral.svg)    **Figure 17** : The grey ellipses are the constant energy trajectories and the **blue curve** is the trajectory of an underdamped oscillator spiraling into the origin.  Energy loss in the damped oscillator", "filename": "14_phaseportraits-tab16-text1.html", "title": "Energy loss in the damped oscillator"}

{"pageid": 7, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@12_motivationforsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@12_motivationforsystems-tab4", "text": "![A curve in the plane with a direction suggesting movement in time. A point on the curve is labeled with x-coordinate x\\(t\\) and y-coordinate y\\(t\\).](/static/images/trajectoryR2.svg)    **Figure 10** : The trajectory of a point in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^2[/mathjaxinline]      The trajectory of a point in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^2[/mathjaxinline] can be represented by the vector function [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} x(t)\\\\\\ y(t) \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]x=x(t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]y=y(t)[/mathjaxinline] are the changing [mathjaxinline]xy[/mathjaxinline]-coordinates of the point at the time [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]. (You may have seen this called a **parametric curve**.)  The entries of a vector may represent other quantities. In the problem we are about to solve on the next page, we'll consider two unknown functions, which are the heights [mathjaxinline]h_1(t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]h_2(t)[/mathjaxinline] of the fluid in two tanks, and represent them as a column vector.  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} h_1(t) \\\\\\ h_2(t) \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This vector function records how both heights evolve over time.  **Derivatives of vector functions**  To find the derivative of a vector, we differentiate each of its components. In particular, the derivative of a vector is another vector with the same number of components.    For example,  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt} \\begin{pmatrix} h_1 \\\\\\ h_2 \\end{pmatrix}=\\begin{pmatrix} \\dot{h_1} \\\\\\ \\dot{h_2} \\end{pmatrix},\\qquad \\text{where }\\, \\, \\dot{h_1} = \\frac{dh_1}{dt} .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      If [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} x\\\\\\ y \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} x(t)\\\\\\ y(t) \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] is the trajectory of a curve, then  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} \\dot x\\\\\\ \\dot y \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      is the velocity vector.  Vector functions", "filename": "12_motivationforsystems-tab4-text1.html", "title": "Vector functions"}

{"pageid": 8, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@12_motivationforsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@12_motivationforsystems-tab3", "text": "### Vectors in Euclidean space  Similarly, a vector in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^n[/mathjaxinline] for any fixed [mathjaxinline]\\, n\\,[/mathjaxinline] corresponds to a point in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^n,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and is usually represented as a column of [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] coordinates.  **Example of a vector in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^3[/mathjaxinline]:**    ![See caption](/static/images/vectorR3.svg)     **Figure 2** : The vector [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ -3 \\\\\\ 8 \\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^3[/mathjaxinline]      Vectors in Euclidean space", "filename": "12_motivationforsystems-tab3-text2.html", "title": "Vectors in Euclidean space"}

{"pageid": 9, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@31_pendulums/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@31_pendulums-tab10", "text": "Let [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} f(x,y) \\\\\\ h(x,y) \\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline] be a function whose input is a vector [mathjaxinline](x,y)[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline]-dimensional space and whose output is also a vector in [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline]-dimensional space.    The **Jacobian matrix** of [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} f(x,y) \\\\\\ h(x,y) \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] is the [mathjaxinline]2\\times 2[/mathjaxinline] matrix-valued function  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{J}(x,y)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} f_x & f_y \\\\\\ h_x & h_y \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.57)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      where [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle f_x=\\frac{\\partial f }{\\partial x}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is the partial derivative of [mathjaxinline]\\, f(x,y)\\,[/mathjaxinline] with respect to [mathjaxinline]x,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and similarly for [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f_y,\\, h_x,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, h_y[/mathjaxinline].  The Jacobian matrix plays the same role for vector-valued functions in multi- variable calculus as the derivative does in single-variable calculus.     **Example 10.1**  Recall the companion system of a unit-mass, unit-length pendulum:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} \\dot{\\theta }\\\\\\ \\dot{\\omega }\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} \\omega \\\\\\ -b\\omega - g \\sin \\theta \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.58)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Find the Jacobian matrix of the vector-valued function on the right hand side of this system.  **Solution** : Let  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(\\theta , \\omega )[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\omega[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.59)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle h(\\theta ,\\omega )[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -b\\omega - g \\sin \\theta[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.60)      Then the Jacobian matrix of the right hand side [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} f(\\theta ,\\omega ) \\\\\\ h(\\theta ,\\omega ) \\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline] of the system is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{J}(\\theta ,\\omega )[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} f_\\theta & f_\\omega \\\\\\ h_\\theta & h_\\omega \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1\\\\\\ -g\\cos (\\theta ) & -b \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.61)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---       **Remark:** The Jacobian matrix requires us to compute 4 partial derivatives. For our purposes, the next crucial step is to evaluate the Jacobian matrix separately at each critical point. The behavior of the matrix can be very different at different critical points. As we saw in the case of the pendulum, one critical point is stable and the other is unstable.     **Warning:** The Jacobian matrix is a matrix. Do not confuse it with the Jacobian determinant, which is also sometimes called the Jacobian. You learned in multivariable calculus that the absolute value of the Jacobian determinant is the area scaling factor when doing a change of variable in a double integral.  The Jacobian matrix", "filename": "31_pendulums-tab10-text2.html", "title": "The Jacobian matrix"}

{"pageid": 11, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@12_motivationforsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@12_motivationforsystems-tab3", "text": "### Vector addition  We add two vectors component-wise:  **Addition example:** [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 2\\\\\\ -2 \\end{pmatrix}+ \\begin{pmatrix} 3\\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix} =\\begin{pmatrix} 5 \\\\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline]  Geometrically, the sum of two vectors is obtained by placing the origin of the second vector at the head of the first vector, as illustrated below:  ![The vector connecting the origin to the point \\(2, negative 2\\) connects to a vector pointing from \\(2, negative 2\\) to \\(5, negative 1\\). {"pageid": 14, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@33_autonomoussystemsstability/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@33_autonomoussystemsstability-tab14", "text": "Next let us redraw the phase portrait for the slightly damped pendulum, so [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{b>0}} .[/mathjaxinline] Recall the system is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\theta }[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\omega[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\omega }[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -b\\omega - \\sin \\theta .[/mathjaxinline] |  |      In this case, the time derivative of the energy function is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{E}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\omega \\dot{\\omega } + (\\sin \\theta ) \\dot{\\theta }[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\omega (-b\\omega -\\sin \\theta ) + (\\sin \\theta ) \\omega[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -b\\omega ^2.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      In other words, energy is lost to friction whenever the mass is moving.    * There are still the stationary trajectories at critical points.     * All other trajectories cross the energy levels, moving to lower energy: the direction field always points \u201cinwards\" towards lower energy; the energy levels serve as fences preventing phase plane motion to higher energy; the trajectory tends to a limit that must be a critical point, one of   [mathjax]\\ldots , \\quad (-2\\pi ,0), \\quad (-\\pi ,0), \\quad (0,0), \\quad (\\pi ,0), \\quad (2\\pi ,0), \\quad \\ldots .[/mathjax]|   ---|---    ![The energy level curves act like fences for the trajectory of a damped pendulum, the trajectory moving almost parallel but inwards towards lower and lower energy levels, ending in a spiral about a stable critical point.](/static/images/u7s2_pendulumdamped.svg)    **Figure 31** : A trajectory of the damped pendulum crossing energy level curves  Phase portrait of the damped pendulum", "filename": "33_autonomoussystemsstability-tab14-text1.html", "title": "Phase portrait of the damped pendulum"}

{"pageid": 15, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab15", "text": "Let us return to example of medicine (or any other fluid) stored in two connected tanks. Recall that you've been put in charge of part of a medicine manufacturing plant with two identical cylindrical storage tanks. The tanks are filled with the medicine to different heights. They are connected to each other via a pipe at their bottoms, with valves that are initially closed. Assume both tanks are in good condition and do not leak. Our goal is to determine how the fluid will flow once we open the valves. To begin, we name the heights [mathjaxinline]h_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]h_2[/mathjaxinline] of the fluid in the two tanks.  ![ ](/static/images/tanks2color_copy.svg)  The system of DEs we [derived in the last lecture](/jump_to_id/12_motivationforsystems-tab6) at was:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dh_1}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle a(h_2-h_1)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dh_2}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle a(h_1-h_2).[/mathjaxinline] |  |      To make things even nicer, we'll assume the parameter [mathjaxinline]\\, a=1\\,[/mathjaxinline] (the effect of setting [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] is just rescaling time). This results in the matrix equation  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt}\\begin{pmatrix} h_1\\\\\\ h_2 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} -1 & 1\\\\\\ 1 & -1 \\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} h_1\\\\\\ h_2 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      **Problem 15.1** Find the general solution to this system and determine its long term behavior.  **Solution:**     **Step 1. Find the eigenvalues.**    To find the eigenvalues of the coefficient matrix, we find the roots of the characteristic polynomial:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{det}\\begin{pmatrix} -1-\\lambda & 1 \\\\\\ 1 & -1-\\lambda \\end{pmatrix} = \\lambda (\\lambda + 2) = 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      We see that the eigenvalues are [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _1 = 0 \\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda _2=-2.[/mathjaxinline]     **Step 2 . Find the eigenvectors.**    The next step in solving the system is to find an eigenvector for each eigenvalue. An eigenvector corresponding to [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _1 = 0[/mathjaxinline] is a nonzero solution to  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} -1 & 1 \\\\\\ 1 & -1 \\end{pmatrix} \\mathbf v_1 = 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      By inspection,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf v_1 = \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      This is the [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v_1[/mathjaxinline] that we expected. It gives a steady state solution which means that the two tanks have the same level of fluid.    Next, we find an eigenvector corresponding to the eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _2=-2[/mathjaxinline]:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 1 \\\\\\ 1 & 1 \\end{pmatrix} \\mathbf v_2 = 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      Again by inspection, the eigenvectors are all (nonzero) scalar multiples of  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf v_2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---      **Step 3. Write down the general solution.**    Therefore, the general solution is:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} h_1(t)\\\\\\ h_2(t) \\end{pmatrix} =c_1\\, \\, \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}+c_2 \\, \\begin{pmatrix} -1\\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}e^{-2t}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      where [mathjaxinline]\\, c_1 \\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, c_2 \\,[/mathjaxinline] are constants.  **Long term behavior from eigenvalues**    The first term [mathjaxinline]\\, c_1 \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] in the general solution is the steady state and also the only constant solution to the system. This is because the term proportional to [mathjaxinline]\\, \\begin{pmatrix} -1\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}e^{-2t}\\,[/mathjaxinline] will decay to zero as [mathjaxinline]\\, t\\,[/mathjaxinline] gets large no matter what [mathjaxinline]\\, c_1\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, c_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] are. This means regardless of the initial conditions, the ratio of the heights in tank 1 and tank 2 will approach the ratio [mathjaxinline]1:1[/mathjaxinline]. This is consistent with what we expect from real life experience: the heights in the two tanks will become equal as the fluid flows between them.    Note that we can deduce just from the eigenvalues alone and without finding the eigenvectors that the system has a steady state determined by the eigenvector of the eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline].  **Problem 15.2** Before opening the valves, we measure the heights of fluid in the 2 tanks. We find that tank 1 is empty, while tank 2 contains 1 meter of fluid in height. Written as a vector equation, this initial condition is:    |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} h_1(0)\\\\\\ h_2(0) \\end{pmatrix}\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.106)   ---|---|---|---      How will the heights of the fluid in the 2 tanks evolve over time?  **Solution:**    The initial condition allows us to determine the unknown scalars in the general solution. Plugging in [mathjaxinline]\\, t=0\\,[/mathjaxinline] in the general solution gives the condition:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} h_1(0)\\\\\\ h_2(0) \\end{pmatrix}\\, =\\, c_1\\, \\, \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}+c_2 \\, \\begin{pmatrix} -1\\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}= \\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.107)   ---|---|---|---      By inspection, [mathjaxinline]\\, c_1=c_2=1/2\\,[/mathjaxinline] solves the equation. (We will learn a systematic way to solve this kind of equation in a later course _Linear algebra and systems of differential equations_.) Therefore, the heights of fluid in the 2 tanks will evolve as follows:    |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} h_1(t)\\\\\\ h_2(t) \\end{pmatrix} =\\frac{1}{2}\\, \\, \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}+\\frac{1}{2} e^{-2t}\\, \\begin{pmatrix} -1\\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      Observe that as [mathjaxinline]\\, t\\,[/mathjaxinline] gets large, the levels in both tanks settle at [mathjaxinline]\\, 1/2\\,[/mathjaxinline] meters, as expected from experience if we had started with 1 meter of fluid in total.    Back to the medicine in connected storage tanks", "filename": "13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab15-text1.html", "title": "Back to the medicine in connected storage tanks"}

{"pageid": 16, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@15_stability/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@15_stability-tab3", "text": "The large collection of [mathjaxinline]2\\times 2[/mathjaxinline] homogeneous first order systems with constant coefficients, [mathjaxinline]\\dot{ \\mathbf{x}}=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x},\\,[/mathjaxinline] is parametrized by the four entries in the matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}.\\,[/mathjaxinline] Two particular combinations of these four parameters, namely the **trace** and the **determinant** , determine much of the qualitative behavior of such systems. This is because the possible types of phase portraits (that we discussed in the last lecture) are determined by the eigenvalues of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A},\\,[/mathjaxinline] which in turn are determined by the characteristic polynomial  [mathjax]\\mathrm{det}( \\mathbf{A}-\\lambda \\mathbf{I}) = {\\color{blue}{\\lambda }} ^2 - (\\mathrm{tr}A) {\\color{blue}{\\lambda }} + (\\mathrm{det}A).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Hence, we will now consider an entire plane with coordinates [mathjaxinline](\\text{Tr},\\text{Det})=(\\mathrm{tr}\\mathbf{A},\\, \\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}),\\,[/mathjaxinline] that is, a plane with the trace on the horizontal axis and the determinant on the vertical axis. Whenever we pick a point on this plane, we will be considering the homogeneous [mathjaxinline]2\\times 2[/mathjaxinline] first order constant coefficient systems [mathjaxinline]\\dot{\\mathbf{x}}=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}\\,[/mathjaxinline] whose matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] has trace [mathjaxinline]\\text{Tr}[/mathjaxinline] and determinant [mathjaxinline]\\text{Det}[/mathjaxinline].  **Remark:** For any given trace-determinant pair [mathjaxinline](\\text{Tr},\\text{Det}),\\,[/mathjaxinline] there are infinitely many matrices [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{tr}\\mathbf{A}=\\text{Tr}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}=\\text{Det}[/mathjaxinline]. One example is the \u201ccompanion matrix,\"  [mathjax]\\mathbf{A}=\\left[\\begin{array}{cc}0& 1\\\\\\ -\\text{Det}& \\text{Tr}\\end{array}\\right].[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This is a particularly important example, because it represents the system corresponding to the LTI equation [mathjaxinline]\\ddot x-(\\text{Tr})\\dot x+(\\text{Det}) x=0[/mathjaxinline], via [mathjaxinline]y=\\dot x[/mathjaxinline].  Introduction", "filename": "15_stability-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Introduction"}

{"pageid": 18, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@12_motivationforsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@12_motivationforsystems-tab11", "text": "**Important note about terminology:** Here we refer to finding a **companion system** or **companion matrix**. In other fields this is referred to as **reduction of order** as you take a higher order differential equation and reduce to a system of first order equations. In engineering (in particular Mechanical Engineering, Electrical Engineering, and Aero/Astro for example), this is called the **state space model** .  In general, we can convert any second order linear ODE into a first order system of linear ODEs. We do so by introducing a new variable for the first derivative and rewriting the DE in terms of the new variable.  Recall (from lecture 11 of the course _Introduction to differential equations_ ) the differential equation for the current in a series RLC circuit with a constant input voltage:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle L\\ddot{I}+R\\dot{I}+\\frac{1}{C}I=0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      where [mathjaxinline]\\, I\\,[/mathjaxinline] is the current, and [mathjaxinline]\\, R,\\, L,\\, C\\,[/mathjaxinline] are the resistance, inductance and capacitance respectively. First divide by [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] to get  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ddot{I}+\\frac{R}{L}\\dot{I}+\\frac{1}{LC}I=0.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      Define a new variable [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] for the first derivative of the current:  [mathjax]y = \\dot{I}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Now the question is what is [mathjaxinline]\\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline]? Using the definition above, we have  [mathjax]\\dot{y}=\\ddot I=-\\frac{1}{LC}I-\\frac{R}{L}\\dot I=-\\frac{1}{LC}I-\\frac{R}{L}y.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      We have done something important. We've rewritten the original differential equation as a **first order equation**.    The last two equations can be written as a [mathjaxinline]2\\times 2[/mathjaxinline] system for the dependent variables [mathjaxinline]\\, I\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, y.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] This is called the **companion system** of the original ODE [mathjaxinline]\\, L\\ddot{I}+R\\dot{I}+\\frac{1}{C} I=0.[/mathjaxinline]  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot I[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\qquad \\quad \\, \\, \\, y[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.39)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -\\frac{1}{LC}I-\\frac{R}{L}y.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.40)      Notice that to obtain the first equation, we have rewritten the defining equation for [mathjaxinline]y,\\,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]y=\\dot I,\\,[/mathjaxinline] by putting the derivative on the left.  Let us write the system in vector notation. Let  |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} I\\\\\\ y\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{\\dot{x}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} \\dot I\\\\\\ \\dot y\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.41)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      Then, by matrix multiplication, the system is  [mathjax]\\mathbf{\\dot{x}}=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x},\\qquad \\text{where }\\, \\mathbf{A}\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\\\\\ -\\frac{1}{LC} & -\\frac{R}{L}\\end{pmatrix}.\\\\\\\\[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] is called the **companion matrix** of the differential operator [mathjaxinline]D^2+\\frac{R}{L}D+\\frac{1}{LC},\\,[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]\\, D\\, =\\, \\frac{d}{dt}[/mathjaxinline].  This is pretty amazing! We have replaced a second order equation with a first order [mathjaxinline]2 \\times 2[/mathjaxinline] system! As we will see shortly, an [mathjaxinline]n^{{\\mathrm{th} }}[/mathjaxinline] order ODE gives rise to a first order [mathjaxinline]n\\times n[/mathjaxinline] system.  We can define a companion system even when there is an inhomogeneous term. Recall (from lecture 11 of the course _Introduction to differential equations_ ) that the DE describing a series RLC circuit with time dependent input voltage [mathjaxinline]V(t)[/mathjaxinline] is  [mathjax]\\ddot I+\\frac{R}{L}\\dot I+\\frac{1}{LC}I=\\frac{\\dot{V}(t)}{L}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This second order ODE translates into the first order [mathjaxinline]\\, 2\\times 2\\,[/mathjaxinline] system  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot I[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\qquad \\qquad \\qquad y[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.42)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -\\frac{1}{LC}I-\\frac{R}{L}y+\\frac{\\dot{V}(t)}{L}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.43)      or in vector notation  [mathjax]\\mathbf{\\dot{x}}=\\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\\\\\ -\\frac{1}{LC} & -\\frac{R}{L}\\end{pmatrix}\\mathbf{x}+\\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ \\frac{\\dot{V}(t)}{L}\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Choice of the new variable:** There is more than one reasonable choice of variables that we can use to define companion systems, but we can always use the first derivative of the unknown in the single differential equation. In the previous example of Newton's second law, we defined the new variable to be momentum, [mathjaxinline]p=m\\dot{x},\\,[/mathjaxinline] but we could have used the velocity [mathjaxinline]\\, y=\\dot x \\,[/mathjaxinline] and would have obtained an equivalent companion system.  ###  Higher-Order Companion Matrices  We can make companion systems for higher order linear differential equations by introducing new function variables for the derivatives.  **Third order systems**  Given a third order linear ODE  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle D^3x+a_2 D^2 x+a_1D x+a_0x=0,\\qquad (D=\\frac{d}{dt})[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      define  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle Dx,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.44)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle z[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle Dy=D^2 x.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.45)      Then the DE can be written as  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle Dz=-a_2z-a_1y-a_0x.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      Therefore, we have a system of three equations, which in vector notation is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt}\\begin{pmatrix} x\\\\\\ y\\\\\\ z\\end{pmatrix}= \\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 1 \\\\\\ -a_0 & -a_1 & -a_2\\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} x\\\\\\ y\\\\\\ z\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] | |   ---|---|---|---      [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{n^{{\\mathrm{th} }}}}[/mathjaxinline] **order systems**  We can do the same thing generally. Given an [mathjaxinline]n^{{\\mathrm{th} }}[/mathjaxinline] order ODE  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle D^nx+a_{n-1}D^{n-1} x+a_{n-2} D^{n-2} x+\\cdots +a_{1}Dx+a_0x=0,[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      define  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_{0}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.46)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_{k}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle D x_{k-1} \\qquad \\text{ for }\\, \\, 0<k\\leq n-1.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.47)      Then the DE can be written as  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle D{x}_{n-1}=-a_{n-1}x_{n-1}-a_{n-2}x_{n-2}-\\cdots -a_{1}x_{1}-a_{0}x_{0}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      Therefore, we have a system of [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] equations, which in vector notation becomes  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt}\\begin{pmatrix} x_0 \\\\\\ x_1 \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ x_{n-2} \\\\\\ x_{n-1}\\end{pmatrix}= \\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 & 0 & \\cdots & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 1 & \\cdots & 0 \\\\\\ \\vdots & \\vdots & \\vdots & \\ddots & \\vdots \\\\\\ 0 & 0 & 0 & \\cdots & 1 \\\\\\ -a_{0} & -a_{1} & -a_{2} & \\cdots & -a_{n-1} \\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} x_0 \\\\\\ x_1 \\\\\\ \\vdots \\\\\\ x_{n-2} \\\\\\ x_{n-1}\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      **Remark:** The dimension of the companion system corresponds to the order of the single ODE we started with.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  The Companion System", "filename": "12_motivationforsystems-tab11-text1.html", "title": "The Companion System"}

{"pageid": 23, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab3", "text": "**Trial solution for 2 by 2 systems**  For a coupled homogenous [mathjaxinline]\\, 2\\times 2\\,[/mathjaxinline] system, each equation depends on both variables, so the solution is not of the form [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle x=C_1 e^{\\lambda _1 t}; y=C_2 e^{\\lambda _2 t}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Rather, we will seek solutions of the form  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} a_1 \\\\\\ a_2 \\end{pmatrix}\\, \\, e^{\\lambda t}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.61)   ---|---|---|---      where [mathjaxinline]\\lambda ,\\,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]a_1,\\, a_2[/mathjaxinline] are the unknowns to be solved for.    Basic solutions", "filename": "13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab3-text2.html", "title": "Basic solutions"}

{"pageid": 24, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@31_pendulums/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@31_pendulums-tab5", "text": "Just as in the linear case, a solution to a general [mathjaxinline]2\\times 2\\,[/mathjaxinline] system is given by two functions of time [mathjaxinline]x(t),\\, y(t),\\,[/mathjaxinline] One can plot this in the [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline]-dimensional [mathjaxinline](t,x,y)[/mathjaxinline]-space, but this may be difficult to draw and to decipher. Therefore, instead, we draw the solution as a **parametrized curve** in the phase plane (or [mathjaxinline](x,y)[/mathjaxinline]-plane).    **Question 5.1** What is the geometric meaning of the autonomous system  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} \\dot{x}(t)\\\\\\ \\dot{y}(t)\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} f(x,y) \\\\\\ h(x,y) \\end{pmatrix}\\quad ?[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.7)   ---|---|---|---|---|---       **Answer:** The vector function [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} x(t)\\\\\\ y(t)\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] describes the motion of the solution on the phase plane. The autonomous system gives the magnitude and direction of the velocity of the motion, [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} \\dot{x}\\\\\\ \\dot{y}\\end{pmatrix}= \\begin{pmatrix} f(x,y)\\\\\\ h(x,y)\\end{pmatrix},\\,[/mathjaxinline] at each point [mathjaxinline]\\left(x,y\\right)[/mathjaxinline] on the plane.    **Example 5.2** Recall the [mathjaxinline]2\\times 2\\,[/mathjaxinline] autonomous system describing a pendulum with unit mass and unit length:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\theta }[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\omega[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.8)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\omega }[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -b\\omega - g \\sin \\theta .[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.9)      What are the velocity vectors at the points [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\left(\\theta ,\\omega \\right) =\\, \\displaystyle \\left(\\frac{\\pi }{2},0\\right)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\left(\\frac{3\\pi }{2},0\\right)[/mathjaxinline]?  **Warning:** Here, we are referring to the velocity vector of the solution in the phase plane. This is different from the velocity or angular velocity of the pendulum mass.  **Solution:** At the point [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\left(\\theta ,\\omega \\right) = \\left(\\frac{\\pi }{2},0\\right)[/mathjaxinline],  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} \\dot{\\theta } \\\\\\ \\dot{\\omega } \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ 0-g\\sin \\left(\\frac{\\pi }{2}\\right)\\end{pmatrix}\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ -g \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.10)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      This velocity vector points downwards and originates from [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left(\\frac{\\pi }{2},0\\right)[/mathjaxinline] on the phase plane.    At the point [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\left(\\theta ,\\omega \\right) = \\left(\\frac{3\\pi }{2},0\\right)[/mathjaxinline],  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} \\dot{\\theta } \\\\\\ \\dot{\\omega } \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 0 -g\\sin \\left(\\frac{3\\pi }{2}\\right)\\end{pmatrix}\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ g \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.11)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      This velocity vector points upwards and originates from [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left(\\frac{3\\pi }{2},0\\right)[/mathjaxinline] on the phase plane.   Since [mathjaxinline]\\, \\omega =\\dot{\\theta },\\,[/mathjaxinline] we do expect that the horizontal components of the velocity vectors [mathjaxinline]\\, \\begin{pmatrix} \\dot{\\theta } \\\\\\ \\dot{\\omega } \\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline] to vanish on the horizontal axis, where [mathjaxinline]\\, \\omega =0.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline]  ### Velocity field  The velocity vectors of the solution at all points on the phase plane comprise a **vector field.** Hence, an autonomous system defines a vector field.    If you draw all the vectors to scale, the picture will become inscrutable! The main use of the velocity field is to help us sketch the trajectories of solutions. This can be done using only the directions of the velocity vectors, and so we will sketch only the direction of the velocity vectors at each point. This sketch is called a **direction field.** Later on, we may not draw the velocity vectors at all, but rather just sketch trajectories with arrow on them indicating the direction of motion.  The mathlet below displays the direction field as well as the phase plane trajectories of a selected set of autonomous systems.    Select the third system from the dropdown menu on the right. This will display the direction field of the companion system of the pendulum.  Check that on the [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]-axis, the vectors point downwards when [mathjaxinline]\\, 0<x<\\pi ,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and point upwards when [mathjaxinline]\\, \\pi <x<2\\pi ,\\,[/mathjaxinline] consistent with the directions we have found above at the points [mathjaxinline]\\left(\\pi /2,0\\right),\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left(3\\pi /2,0\\right).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Move around the plane by clicking the \u201cdrag axis\" button on the right and then drag on the plane, and zoom in and out using the scale slider at the bottom of the phase plane.  Look at the trajectories of the other systems in the mathlet by clicking on points on the phase plane. You can unclick the \u201cVector field\" button to hide the vector field. Notice that  **trajectories never cross!**      This is the consequence of an existence and uniqueness theorem for systems of non-linear ODEs similar to that for a single ODE. For an autonomous system, it implies that there is a unique trajectory through each point (in a region where the partial derivatives of [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline] are continuous).  ###  Comparison with slope field  Recall (from the course _introduction to differential equations_ ) that a single non-linear differential equation  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(t,x)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.12)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      defines a slope field by giving the value of the slope [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\frac{dx}{dt}\\,[/mathjaxinline] of the solution curve at each point on the [mathjaxinline](t,x)[/mathjaxinline]-plane. Here, time [mathjaxinline]\\, t\\,[/mathjaxinline] is the independent variable, and [mathjaxinline]\\, x\\,[/mathjaxinline] is the dependent variable, the system response that we are interested in.   A picture of the slope field consists of short line segments, with no direction, depicting the slope of [mathjaxinline]\\, x(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] at each point. Any curve that is tangent to the slope field at each time [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] is a solution curve. Recall that for an autonomous DE [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}=f(x),\\,[/mathjaxinline] the slope field is invariant under time translation.    On the other hand, the direction field discussed above, defined by the direction of the vector [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\left(f(x,y), g(x,y)\\right)\\,[/mathjaxinline] at each point [mathjaxinline]\\, (x,y),\\,[/mathjaxinline] indicates the direction in which the solution moves in the phase plane as [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] increases. A curve along this direction field is a trajectory of a solution on the phase plane. It does not capture all information of a solution since it does not show how fast the solution is moving in time. the large regions in the trace-determinant plane, which correspond to saddles, nodes, and spirals, then the phase portrait of the **original nonlinear system near** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{(a,b)}}[/mathjaxinline] looks like the phase portrait of the **linearized system near** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{(0,0)}}[/mathjaxinline]. (We will not prove this, or even make precise what \u201clooks like\" means.)    Recall the structurally unstable cases are borderline cases: the positive vertical axis, the parabola, and the horizontal axis. For example, if the linearized system is on the critical parabola, the nonlinear system could behave like a spiral, a node, or something in between.  ![Trace determinant plane with Trace along the horizontal axis and Determinant along the vertical axis. Along these boundaries are exactly where a system is structurally unstable.](/static/images/u3s4_tdfull.svg)  **Warning:** Even when the linearized system is structurally stable, the phase portrait of the nonlinear system may become more and more warped as one moves away from the critical point.     **Warning:** Remember that stability and structural stability are different concepts.    * **Stable** means that all nearby solutions tend to the critical point.     * **Structurally stable** means that the phase portrait type is robust, unaffected by small changes in the entries of the matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 27, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@33_autonomoussystemsstability/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@33_autonomoussystemsstability-tab7", "text": "**Problem 7.1** Sketch the phase portrait for the deer-wolf system  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 3x-x^2 -xy[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y-y^2+xy.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      **Solution:**  ###  Review: linearization, stability, and structural stability at the critical points  We have already found the 4 critical points:  [mathjax](0,0), \\quad (0,1), \\quad (3,0), \\quad (1,2).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and the Jacobian matrix of the system:  [mathjax]\\mathbf{J}(x,y) = \\begin{pmatrix} 3-2x-y & -x \\\\\\ y & 1-2y+x \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Let us review the linearization near each critical point.    **Critical point** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{(1,2)}}[/mathjaxinline] **:**  [mathjax]\\mathbf{J}(1,2) = \\begin{pmatrix} -1 & -1 \\\\\\ 2 & -2 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This has trace [mathjaxinline]-3[/mathjaxinline] and determinant [mathjaxinline]4[/mathjaxinline], so this critical point is **stable** .  The characteristic polynomial is [mathjaxinline]\\lambda ^2+3\\lambda +4[/mathjaxinline], and the eigenvalues are [mathjaxinline]\\frac{-3 \\pm \\sqrt{-7}}{2}[/mathjaxinline]. These are complex numbers with negative real part, so this describes an **spiral sink** . The velocity vector at [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} X\\\\\\ Y \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} -1 \\\\\\ 2 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline], so the spiral is counterclockwise.    This is a **structurally stable** case, so the phase portrait for the original nonlinear system near [mathjaxinline](1,2)[/mathjaxinline] will be a counterclockwise spiral sink too.     **Critical point** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{(0,0)}}[/mathjaxinline] **:**  [mathjax]\\mathbf{J}(0,0) = \\begin{pmatrix} 3 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 1 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This has trace [mathjaxinline]4[/mathjaxinline], so this critical point is **unstable** .    Since the matrix is diagonal, its eigenvalues are the diagonal entries [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline], and corresponding eigenvectors are [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] The eigenvalues are distinct positive real numbers, so this describes a **nodal source** . Most trajectories (except the ones on the [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline]-eigenline) emanating from [mathjaxinline](0,0)[/mathjaxinline] are tangent to the [mathjaxinline]Y[/mathjaxinline]-axis.    This is a **structurally stable** case, so the phase portrait for the original system near [mathjaxinline](0,0)[/mathjaxinline] too will be a nodal source, and most trajectories (except the ones on the [mathjaxinline]3[/mathjaxinline]-eigenline) emanating from [mathjaxinline](0,0)[/mathjaxinline] are tangent to the [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]-axis.     **Critical point** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{(0,1)}}[/mathjaxinline] **:**  [mathjax]\\mathbf{J}(0,1) = \\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 0 \\\\\\ 1 & -1 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This has trace [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline], so this critical point is **unstable** .    Since the matrix is lower triangular, its eigenvalues are the diagonal entries [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline]. The eigenvalues are real numbers of opposite sign, so this describes a **saddle** . The eigenlines for the eigenvalues [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline] are [mathjaxinline]Y=\\frac{1}{3} X[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]X=0[/mathjaxinline].    This is a **structurally stable** case, so the phase portrait for the original system near [mathjaxinline](0,1)[/mathjaxinline] is a saddle too.  **Critical point** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{(3,0)}}[/mathjaxinline] **:**  [mathjax]\\mathbf{J}(3,0) = \\begin{pmatrix} -3 & -3 \\\\\\ 0 & 4 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This has trace [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline], so this critical point is **unstable** .    Since the matrix is upper triangular, its eigenvalues are the diagonal entries [mathjaxinline]-3[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]4[/mathjaxinline]. The eigenvalues are real numbers of opposite sign, so this describes a **saddle** . The eigenlines for the eigenvalues [mathjaxinline]-3[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]4[/mathjaxinline] are [mathjaxinline]Y=0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]Y=-\\frac{7}{3}X[/mathjaxinline].    This is a **structurally stable** case, so the phase portrait for the original system near [mathjaxinline](3,0)[/mathjaxinline] is a saddle too.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Let us ask two further questions that will help in sketching the phase portrait of the full nonlinear system.      1. At which points are the trajectories vertical?        Trajectories are vertical (or stationary) at the points where [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{x}=0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] i.e. where  [mathjax]\\dot{x}=3x-x^2 -xy = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Factoring shows that these are the points on the lines [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]3-x-y=0[/mathjaxinline]. So in the phase portrait we draw little vertical segments at points on these lines. In particular, there will be trajectories along [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline], and we can plot them using the [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline]-dimensional phase line methods, by sampling the velocity vector at one point in each interval created by the critical points. The line [mathjaxinline]3-x-y=0[/mathjaxinline] does not contain trajectories, however, since that line has slope [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline], while trajectories are vertical as they pass through these points.    2. At which points are the trajectories horizontal?        Trajectories are horizontal (or stationary) at the points where [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{y}=0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] i.e. where  [mathjax]\\dot{y}=y-y^2+xy = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      These are the lines [mathjaxinline]y=0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]1-y+x=0[/mathjaxinline], so draw little horizontal segments at points on these lines. Again we can study trajectories along [mathjaxinline]y=0[/mathjaxinline] using [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline]-dimensional phase line methods.  **Big picture:**  ![We describe trajectories that start with positive populations only. Trajectories near the unstable node at the origin start parallel to the vertical axis, and then curve towards being parallel with the x axis before being swept into a spiral about the stable critical point \\(1,2\\). Trajectories near the unstable saddle at \\(0,1\\) begin parallel to the vertical axis, move towards the point \\(0,1\\), then move parallel to the other eigenline before being swept into a spiral about the stable critical point \\(1,2\\). Points near the unstable saddle at \\(3,0\\) begin parallel to the horizontal axis moving towards \\(3,0\\), then turn parallel to the other eigenline before being swept into a spiral sink about the critical point \\(1,2\\).](/static/images/u7s2_deerwolf.svg)  You can reproduce the phase portrait using the mathlet below by selecting the second system in the dropdown menu:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (a+bx+cy)x[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.131)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (d+fx+hy)y[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.132)      and using the sliders to choose the appropriate values for the parameters [mathjaxinline]\\, (a=3,\\, b=-1,\\, c=-1,\\, d=1,\\, f=1,\\, h=-1).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline]    (To have a better view, use the slider below the phase portrait to zoom and click on the \u201cdrag axes\" button and drag to the first quadrant.)  Example: Phase Portrait of the Deer-wolf System", "filename": "33_autonomoussystemsstability-tab7-text2.html", "title": "Example: Phase Portrait of the Deer-wolf System"}

{"pageid": 28, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@15_stability/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@15_stability-tab9", "text": "On the critical parabola, [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}= (\\mathrm{tr}^2)\\mathbf{A}/4,\\,[/mathjaxinline] the systems have a repeated real eigenvalue. When the eigenvalue is repeated, there are two possibilities for the space of eigenvectors. The space of all eigenvectors for this only eigenvalue may be [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline]- or [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline]-dimensional. Depending on whether the repeated eigenvalue is nonzero or zero, and whether the space of eigenvectors is [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline]- or [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline]- dimensional, the phase portraits are different, as follows.  Suppose that there is a **repeated real eigenvalue,** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\lambda _1=\\lambda ,\\, \\lambda _2=\\lambda .\\, \\, }}[/mathjaxinline]The space of eigenvectors of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda \\,[/mathjaxinline] could be either [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline]-dimensional or [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline]-dimensional.    1. **Degenerate node** (or **improper node** or **defective node** ):    **Repeated nonzero eigenvalue** with **1-dimensional** space of eigenvectors, [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\lambda \\ne 0}}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{A}\\ne \\lambda \\mathbf{I}}} .[/mathjaxinline]  There is just one eigenline.  Every trajectory not contained in the eigenline becomes tangent to it at [mathjaxinline](0,0)[/mathjaxinline], and becomes parallel to it when far away from [mathjaxinline](0,0)[/mathjaxinline]. Such trajectories are      * repelled from [mathjaxinline](0,0)[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]\\lambda >0[/mathjaxinline],       * attracted to [mathjaxinline](0,0)[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]\\lambda <0[/mathjaxinline].   This is a borderline case between a node and a spiral.  **Example of solution:**  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{x}= c_1\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix} e^t+ c_2\\left(\\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}e^t+\\begin{pmatrix} 2\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}te^t\\right)[/mathjaxinline]  | ![Degenerate node looks similar to a spiral except there is only one eigenline. Solutions start parallel to this eigenline pointing in one direction for large negative times, but tend to the same eigenline pointed in the opposite direction for large positive times.](/static/images/u3s4_dnode.svg)   ---|---     2. **Star Node:**    **Repeated nonzero eigenvalue, 2-dimensional space of eigenvectors** , [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\lambda \\ne 0}}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{A}= \\lambda \\mathbf{I}}} .[/mathjaxinline]  Every nonzero vector is an eigenvector.  Nonzero trajectories are along rays, and are      * repelled from [mathjaxinline](0,0)[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]\\lambda >0[/mathjaxinline],       * attracted to [mathjaxinline](0,0)[/mathjaxinline] if [mathjaxinline]\\lambda <0[/mathjaxinline].   **General solution:** [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}= e^{\\lambda t}\\left[c_1\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}+c_2\\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}\\right].[/mathjaxinline]  | ![Every vector is an eigenvector. In this example, trajectories start at origin for large negative times, and point outwards in lines in every direction as time increases.](/static/images/u3s4_star.svg)   ---|---    At the origin of the trace-determinant plane, both eigenvalues are zero. There are two kinds of phase portraits, depending on the dimension of the space of eigenvectors.    1. **Repeated zero eigenvalue** with **1-dimensional** space of eigenvectors, [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\lambda = 0}}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{A}\\ne \\mathbf{0}}} .[/mathjaxinline] There is only one eigenline. Points on the eigenline are stationary. All other trajectories are lines parallel to the eigenline.   **General solution:** [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}= c_1\\mathbf v+ c_2\\left(t\\mathbf v+\\mathbf{w}\\right) \\,[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v\\,[/mathjaxinline] is an eigenvector of [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] and the constant vector [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{w}\\,[/mathjaxinline] satisfies [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v=(\\mathbf{A}-\\lambda \\mathbf{I})\\mathbf{w}[/mathjaxinline].    2. **Repeated zero eigenvalue** with **2-dimensional** space of eigenvectors, [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\lambda = 0}}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{A}=\\mathbf{0}}} .[/mathjaxinline]   Every solution is a **stationary point**.  **General solution:** [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}= \\begin{pmatrix} c_1 \\\\\\ c_2 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline].  On the critical parabola", "filename": "15_stability-tab9-text1.html", "title": "On the critical parabola"}

{"pageid": 30, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@33_autonomoussystemsstability/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@33_autonomoussystemsstability-tab13", "text": "**Energy level** [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{E\\, =\\, 2}} \\,[/mathjaxinline] **:**  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{2} \\omega ^2 + (1-\\cos \\theta )[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 2[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{2} \\omega ^2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 1 + \\cos \\theta[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 1 + (2 \\cos ^2 \\frac{\\theta }{2} - 1)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 2 \\cos ^2 \\frac{\\theta }{2}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\quad \\omega[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\pm 2 \\cos \\frac{\\theta }{2}.[/mathjaxinline] | |      Does this mean that the motion is periodic, going around and around? No. This energy level contains three physical trajectories:  ![Energy level 2 starts from one unstable critical point and moves in an arc to the adjacent unstable critical point. These correspond to trajectories where the pendulum starts at the top of the cricle, moves around the circle and stops at the top. ](/static/images/u7s2_pendulumE2.svg)    **Figure 28** : Trajectories with [mathjaxinline]\\, E=2\\,[/mathjaxinline].    * one in which the pendulum mass is stationary at the top, which corresponds to the critical points at [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left((2n+1)\\pi ,0\\right)\\,[/mathjaxinline]     * one in which the mass does one counterclockwise loop as [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] goes from [mathjaxinline]-\\infty[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\infty[/mathjaxinline], slowing down as it approaches the top, taking infinitely long to get there (and infinitely long to come from there). Since, [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] is increasing as [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] increases, this corresponds to the arc in the upper half phase plane originating from [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left(-\\pi ,0\\right)\\,[/mathjaxinline] and tending towards [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left(\\pi ,0\\right),\\,[/mathjaxinline] (and its horizontal shifts by [mathjaxinline]2n\\pi[/mathjaxinline]),     * the same, except clockwise, which corresponds to the arc in the lower half phase plane originating from [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left(\\pi ,0\\right)\\,[/mathjaxinline] and tending towards [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left(-\\pi ,0\\right),\\,[/mathjaxinline] (and its horizontal shifts [mathjaxinline]2n\\pi[/mathjaxinline]).   In the last two cases, the mass can't actually reach the top, since its phase plane trajectory can't touch the stationary trajectory.      **Energy level** [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{E=3}} \\,[/mathjaxinline] **:**  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{2} \\omega ^2 + (1-\\cos \\theta )[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 3[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\quad \\omega[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\pm \\sqrt{4 + 2 \\cos \\theta }.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The possibility [mathjaxinline]\\omega = \\sqrt{4 + 2 \\cos \\theta }[/mathjaxinline] is a periodic function of [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline], varying between [mathjaxinline]\\sqrt{2}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\sqrt{6}[/mathjaxinline]. The energy level consists of two trajectories: in each, the weight makes it to the top still having some kinetic energy, so that it keeps going around (either clockwise or counterclockwise).  ![Energy level 3 are two wavy lines \\(one above the horizontal axis and one below\\) that curve outwards away from stable critical point and inwards towards unstable critical points.](/static/images/u7s2_pendulumE3.svg)    **Figure 29** : Trajectories with [mathjaxinline]\\, E=3\\,[/mathjaxinline]  Here is a sketch of the full phase portrait:  ![See caption](/static/images/u7s2_pendulumfull.svg)    **Figure 30** : Trajectories with [mathjaxinline]\\, E = 0, 1/8, 1, 2, 3, 5[/mathjaxinline]  Energy Levels Continued", "filename": "33_autonomoussystemsstability-tab13-text2.html", "title": "Energy Levels Continued"}
