{"pageid": 32, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@15_stability/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@15_stability-tab7", "text": "We have seen that the big regions on the trace-determinant plane correspond to nodes, saddles, and spirals. What are the system behaviors on the boundaries of these regions? These cases are called **degenerate** cases. So far, we know that systems on the upper vertical axis are centers. But what happens on the horizontal [mathjaxinline]\\text{Tr}[/mathjaxinline]-axis, or on the critical parabola? Let us start with the horizontal axis.    ![Boundaries of Trace Determinant plane that separate the six regions of behavior are the entire horizontal Trace axis, the critical parabola, and the positive Det axis. These boundaries all intersect at the origin.](/static/images/u3s4_tdsemifull.svg)     **Figure 18** : Systems on the **boundaries** between regions are the degenerate cases.      On the horizontal [mathjaxinline]\\text{Tr}[/mathjaxinline]-axis, [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}=\\lambda _1\\lambda _2=0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] so one of the eigenvalues is zero. The other eigenvalue is nonzero except at the origin, since [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathrm{tr}\\mathbf{A}=\\lambda _1+\\lambda _2.\\,[/mathjaxinline]     **Example 7.1**  Recall the system describing two connected non-leaking fluid storage tanks:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt}\\begin{pmatrix} h_1\\\\\\ h_2 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} -1 & 1\\\\\\ 1 & -1 \\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} h_1\\\\\\ h_2 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.78)   ---|---|---|---      where [mathjaxinline]\\, h_1,\\, h_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] are the heights of fluid in the two tanks.    We have previously found the eigenvalue-eigenvector pairs:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\lambda _1=0[/mathjaxinline] | |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf v_1=\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.79)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda _2=-2[/mathjaxinline] |  | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf v_2=\\begin{pmatrix} -1\\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.80)      Note that one of the eigenvalues is [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]. This gives the general solution  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} h_1(t)\\\\\\ h_2(t) \\end{pmatrix} =c_1\\, \\, \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}+c_2 \\, \\begin{pmatrix} -1\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}e^{-2t}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.81)   ---|---|---|---      What are the phase plane trajectories of this system?  **Solution:**     **On the [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]-eigenline:**    The trajectory of the solution [mathjaxinline]\\, c_1\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a **stationary point** on the [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]-eigenline.  ![See text above](/static/images/u3s4_noleaktankpt.svg)    **Figure 19** : A stationary point as the trajectory of [mathjaxinline]\\, c_1\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline]  The location of the point on the line depends on the value of [mathjaxinline]\\, c_1.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Since every point on the [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]-eigenline is a stationary point, such a point is also called a **non-isolated critical point** .  **On the eigenline with negative eigenvalue:**   The trajectory of the solution [mathjaxinline]\\, c_2 \\begin{pmatrix} -1\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}e^{-2t}\\,[/mathjaxinline] moves towards the origin on the [mathjaxinline]-2[/mathjaxinline] eigenline.  ![See text above](/static/images/u3s4_noleaktankeigenline.svg)    **Other trajectories:**   The trajectory of the solution [mathjaxinline]\\, c_1\\\\! \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}+c_2\\\\! \\begin{pmatrix} -1\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}e^{-2t}\\,[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]\\, c_1,c_2\\neq 0\\,[/mathjaxinline] will approach the point [mathjaxinline]\\, c_1\\, \\, \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline] as the term [mathjaxinline]\\, c_2 \\, \\begin{pmatrix} -1\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}e^{-2t}\\,[/mathjaxinline] decays to [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]\\, t\\to \\infty[/mathjaxinline]. It moves along a line that is parallel to the [mathjaxinline]-2[/mathjaxinline]-eigenline and approaches the [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]-eigenline at the point [mathjaxinline]\\, c_1\\, \\, \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}.\\,[/mathjaxinline] Which side of the [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]-eigenline the trajectory is on depends on the sign of [mathjaxinline]c_2[/mathjaxinline].  ![See text above](/static/images/u3s4_noleaktank1line.svg)    **Figure 20** : Trajectory of [mathjaxinline]\\, 2\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix} + \\begin{pmatrix} -1\\\\\\ 1\\end{pmatrix}e^{-2t}\\,[/mathjaxinline]      The phase portrait therefore looks like the following two-sided **comb** :  ![See text above](/static/images/u3s4_noleaktankpp.svg)  **Remark:** The stationary point solution on the [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]-eigenline corresponds to constant solutions in which the starting heights of the fluid are equal.  ![Two connected fluid tanks start with fluid of same height in both tanks does not change over time, and ends with fluid at same height.](/static/images/u3s4_2tanksequal.svg)  Other trajectories correspond to solutions that start with different heights but approach equal heights as time passes.  ![Two connected fluid tanks start with fluid of different heights, but tends to having fluid at same height in both tanks.](/static/images/u3s4_2tanks.svg)  Degenerate cases: comb", "filename": "15_stability-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Degenerate cases: comb"}

{"pageid": 33, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@12_motivationforsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@12_motivationforsystems-tab10", "text": "Let us revisit Newton's second law:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle m\\ddot{x}=F.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      Recall that momentum is defined as [mathjaxinline]p= m\\dot{x}.[/mathjaxinline] In terms of momentum, Newton's second law becomes  [mathjax]\\dot{p}=F \\qquad (p=m\\dot{x}).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Assume [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline] is a function of the position [mathjaxinline]x.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] We can write Newton's second law as a **first order system** using position [mathjaxinline]x\\,[/mathjaxinline] and momentum [mathjaxinline]p[/mathjaxinline] as the dependent variables:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{p}{m}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{p}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F(x).[/mathjaxinline] |  |      For example, in the case of a simple harmonic oscillator, the force is the spring force [mathjaxinline]F=-kx,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and the system we obtain is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{p}{m}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{p}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -kx.[/mathjaxinline] |  |  Newton's Second Law", "filename": "12_motivationforsystems-tab10-text1.html", "title": "Newton's Second Law"}

{"pageid": 36, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@31_pendulums/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@31_pendulums-tab9", "text": "The second step in sketching the solutions to a [mathjaxinline]2 \\times 2\\,[/mathjaxinline] autonomous non-linear system is to linearize the system at each critical point and sketch the trajectories near it.    The **Linearization of an autonomous system**  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} \\dot{x}\\\\\\ \\dot{y}\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} f(x,y) \\\\\\ h(x,y) \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.34)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      near a point means to replace both [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline] by their linear approximations near that point.  **Example 9.1** Recall the [mathjaxinline]2\\times 2\\,[/mathjaxinline] autonomous system describing a pendulum:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\theta }[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\omega[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.35)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\omega }[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -b\\omega - g \\sin \\theta .[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.36)      Find the linearization of this system near the origin [mathjaxinline](\\theta ,\\omega ) =(0, 0)[/mathjaxinline].  **Solution:** We need to find the linear approximation near [mathjaxinline](0,0)[/mathjaxinline] of the right hand sides of each equation. The first equation is already linear, [mathjaxinline]\\dot\\theta = \\omega .[/mathjaxinline]    The second equation is non-linear due to the [mathjaxinline]\\, \\sin (\\theta )\\,[/mathjaxinline] term. Since the linear approximation to [mathjaxinline]\\sin (\\theta )[/mathjaxinline] near [mathjaxinline]\\theta = 0[/mathjaxinline] is given by [mathjaxinline]\\sin (\\theta )\\sim \\theta ,\\,[/mathjaxinline] the linearized equation is :  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\omega }[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -b\\omega - g \\theta .[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.37)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      In matrix notation, the two linearized equations can be written as:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} \\dot{\\theta } \\\\\\ \\dot{\\omega } \\end{pmatrix} = \\mathbf{A}\\begin{pmatrix} \\theta \\\\\\ \\omega \\end{pmatrix} \\qquad \\text{where }\\, \\, \\mathbf{A}\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1\\\\\\ -g & -b \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      **Question 9.2** Suppose that the damping is small, that is, [mathjaxinline]\\, b< 2\\sqrt{g}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] What is the phase portrait of the linearization of the system near the origin?  **Solution** : The characteristic polynomial of the linearized system near the origin is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\lambda ^2-(\\mathrm{tr}\\mathbf{A}) \\lambda +\\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}=\\lambda ^2+b\\lambda +g,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.38)   ---|---|---|---      whose roots are the eigenvalues  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\lambda[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -\\frac{b}{2}\\pm \\frac{\\sqrt{b^2-4g}}{2}\\, =\\, -\\frac{b}{2}\\pm \\frac{i\\sqrt{4g-b^2}}{2}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.39)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Since the damping is small, that is, [mathjaxinline]\\, b<2\\sqrt{g},\\,[/mathjaxinline] the eigenvalues are complex. The real part of both eigenvalues are negative. Therefore, the phase portrait of the linearized system is a spiral sink.  In the mathlet below, select again the third system from the dropdown menu. This will display the direction field of the pendulum system. Use the slider on the top right to set [mathjaxinline]\\, a=2\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, b<2\\sqrt{a}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Click on points near the origin to display trajectories near the origin. Do you see a spiral sink?  Now vary the value of the damping constant [mathjaxinline]\\, b\\,[/mathjaxinline] while fixing [mathjaxinline]\\, a=2\\,[/mathjaxinline] and watch how the phase portrait changes. For what value of [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] does the spiral sink become a nodal sink? Is this what you expect?  Linear approximation in 2D", "filename": "31_pendulums-tab9-text2.html", "title": "Linear approximation in 2D"}

{"pageid": 38, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@12_motivationforsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@12_motivationforsystems-tab3", "text": "The first step to solving a system of linear DEs is to rewrite it as a **vector equation.** To do this, we will first review basic vector and matrix arithmetic.  ### Vectors in the plane  ![Vector pointing from the origin to the point \\(negative 2, 1\\) in the second quadrant](/static/images/vectorR2.svg)     **Figure 1** : A vector (blue) in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^2[/mathjaxinline]      Geometrically, a vector in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^2[/mathjaxinline] is an arrow from the origin to a point on the plane, and therefore is determined by the [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]- and [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]-coordinates of the point.  We often represent a vector in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^2[/mathjaxinline] by writing the two coordinates in a column, with the [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]-coordinate as the top/first entry, and the [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]-coordinate as the bottom/second entry. A vector represented as a column is called a **column vector** .  Here is the vector in figure above as a column vector: [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} -2 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline].  Vectors and matrices", "filename": "12_motivationforsystems-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Vectors and matrices"}

{"pageid": 39, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@31_pendulums/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@31_pendulums-tab7", "text": "If you remember nothing else from single-variable calculus, remember this:  > If a problem you are trying to solve is too difficult because it involves a > non-linear function [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline], use the best linear > approximation near the most relevant [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]-value > [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{a}}[/mathjaxinline]; that approximation is > [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{f(a)}} + {\\color{blue}{f'(a)}} \\; > (x-{\\color{blue}{a}} )[/mathjax]|   > ---|---   > since this linear polynomial has the same value and same derivative at > [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{a}}[/mathjaxinline] as > [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline].  If you remember nothing else from multivariable calculus, remember this:  > If a problem you are trying to solve is too difficult because it involves a > non-linear function [mathjaxinline]f(x,y)[/mathjaxinline], use the best > linear approximation near the most relevant point > [mathjaxinline]({\\color{blue}{a}} ,{\\color{blue}{b}} )[/mathjaxinline]: that > approximation is [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{f(a,b)}} + > {\\color{blue}{\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial x}(a,b)}} \\; (x- {\\color{blue}{a}} > ) + {\\color{blue}{\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial y}(a,b)}} \\; > (y-{\\color{blue}{b}} )[/mathjax]|   > ---|---   > since this linear polynomial has the same value and same partial derivatives > at [mathjaxinline]({\\color{blue}{a}} ,{\\color{blue}{b}} )[/mathjaxinline] as > [mathjaxinline]f(x,y)[/mathjaxinline].  (The expressions in **blue** are numbers.)  Linear approximation in 2D", "filename": "31_pendulums-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Linear approximation in 2D"}

{"pageid": 40, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@31_pendulums/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@31_pendulums-tab9", "text": "**Stability of a critical point**    The stability of a critical point is determined by the stability of the linearization of the system at that point.  **Definition 9.3** A critical point is called **stable** **(unstable)** if the linearized system at that point is **stable** **(unstable).**    **Example 9.4** For the pendulum, the origin [mathjaxinline]\\, (0,0)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a stable critical point. This corresponds to the fact that if the pendulum mass is near the bottom, it will tend to the rest position at the bottom.  stability", "filename": "31_pendulums-tab9-text3.html", "title": "stability"}

{"pageid": 41, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@15_romance/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@15_romance-tab5", "text": "Suppose Juliet is a straightforward girl: if she likes Romeo, that causes her to like him even more. If Romeo likes her, she likes him more.  But Romeo is more complicated. If he likes her, that causes him to like her even more. That is normal. But if he sees that she is starting to like him, well, that exerts a negative influence on his feelings towards her.  This is modeled by the equations:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot R[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle R-J[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.110)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot J[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle R+J,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.111)      that is,  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} \\dot R\\\\\\ \\dot J\\end{pmatrix}=\\begin{pmatrix} 1& -1\\\\\\ 1& 1\\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} R\\\\\\ J\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Example 5: Responsive and contrary", "filename": "15_romance-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Example 5: Responsive and contrary"}

{"pageid": 42, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@14_phaseportraits/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@14_phaseportraits-tab12", "text": "Suppose that the eigenvalues [mathjaxinline]\\lambda =s+i\\omega ,\\, \\overline{\\lambda }=s-i\\omega[/mathjaxinline] are **complex with nonzero real and imaginary parts.**  Let [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} a_1\\\\\\ a_2\\end{pmatrix} +i\\begin{pmatrix} b_1\\\\\\ b_2\\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline] be the eigenvector of [mathjaxinline]\\lambda =s+i\\omega ,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\overline{\\mathbf v}\\,[/mathjaxinline] be the eigenvector of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\overline{\\lambda }.[/mathjaxinline]    The general **real** solution is of the form  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{x}(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle C_1 \\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left(\\mathbf ve^{\\lambda t}\\right) + C_2 \\mathrm{Im\\, }\\left(\\mathbf ve^{\\lambda t}\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.56)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle C_1 \\left[\\begin{pmatrix} a_1\\\\\\ a_2 \\end{pmatrix} \\cos (\\omega t) -\\begin{pmatrix} b_1\\\\\\ b_2 \\end{pmatrix} \\sin (\\omega t)\\right] e^{st} + C_2 \\left[ \\begin{pmatrix} a_1\\\\\\ a_2 \\end{pmatrix} \\sin (\\omega t) +\\begin{pmatrix} b_1\\\\\\ b_2 \\end{pmatrix} \\cos (\\omega t)\\right] e^{st}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.57)   |  |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (s,\\, \\omega ,\\, a_1,\\, a_2,\\, b_1,\\, b_2,\\, C_1,\\, C_2 \\, \\text{real}).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.58)      Depending on whether the real part [mathjaxinline]\\, s\\,[/mathjaxinline] of the eigenvalue is positive or negative, the phase portrait is either a spiral source or an spiral sink. The number [mathjaxinline]s[/mathjaxinline] controls repulsion/attraction, while [mathjaxinline]\\, \\omega \\,[/mathjaxinline] controls rotation (angular frequency).      1.  **Spiral source** (or **repelling spiral** ): Eigenvalues are complex and have **positive real part,** [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda ,\\overline{\\lambda }=s\\pm \\omega i,\\, {\\color{blue}{s>0}}[/mathjaxinline].    All nonzero trajectories **spiral outward**.  **Example solution:** [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}= \\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left[ \\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\\\\\ -i \\end{pmatrix} e^{(1+3i)t}\\right][/mathjaxinline]  [mathjaxinline]\\qquad = \\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\cos 3t \\\\\\ \\sin 3t \\end{pmatrix}e^{t}.[/mathjaxinline]  | ![Multiple non-crossing trajectories that start near the origin and spiral counterclockwise outwards](/static/images/u3s3_rspiral.svg)   ---|---     2. **Spiral sink** (or **attracting spiral** ): Eigenvalues are complex and have **negative real part,** [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda ,\\, \\overline{\\lambda }=s\\pm \\omega i,\\, {\\color{blue}{s<0}}[/mathjaxinline].    All nonzero trajectories **spiral inward**.  **Example solution:** [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}= \\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left[ \\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\\\\\ -i \\end{pmatrix}e^{(-1+3i)t} \\right][/mathjaxinline]  [mathjaxinline]\\qquad = \\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\cos 3t \\\\\\ \\sin 3t \\end{pmatrix}e^{-t}.[/mathjaxinline]  | ![Multiple non-crossing trajectories that spiral counterclockwise inwards towards the origin](/static/images/u3s3_aspiral.svg)   ---|---    **Question 12.1** Do the trajectories go clockwise or counterclockwise?  **Answer:** It is complicated to see this in terms of eigenvalues and eigenvectors, but easy to see by testing a single velocity vector! At each point [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{x}\\,[/mathjaxinline] on the phase plane, the direction of the trajectory is given by the velocity vector [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}[/mathjaxinline]. For example, at the point [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{x}= \\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix},\\,[/mathjaxinline]  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\mathbf{x}} = \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}= \\mathbf{A}\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.59)   ---|---|---|---      ![A trajectory spiraling away from origin passes through the point \\(1, 0\\). At that point, the vector tangent to the trajectory along the direction of motion is dot x, which is pointing up and away from origin, signaling counterclockwise motion.](/static/images/u3s3_counterclockwise.svg)  The trajectory goes upwards at the point [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{x}=\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline] and is counterclockwise **if and only if** the [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]-coordinate of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}\\,[/mathjaxinline] there is positive.   The direction is the same for all trajectories.  Phase portraits of systems with complex eigenvalues", "filename": "14_phaseportraits-tab12-text1.html", "title": "Phase portraits of systems with complex eigenvalues"}

{"pageid": 43, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab8", "text": "The first step in solving the [mathjaxinline]2\\times 2[/mathjaxinline] system [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is to find the eigenvalues of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}.[/mathjaxinline]     **Example 8.1** Find all the eigenvalues of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}= \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & -2 \\\\\\ -1 & 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline].  **Solution:**  The characteristic polynomial is  [mathjax]P(\\lambda ) = \\mathrm{det}(\\mathbf{A}-\\lambda \\mathbf{I}) = \\mathrm{det}\\begin{pmatrix} 1-\\lambda & -2 \\\\\\ -1 & -\\lambda \\end{pmatrix} = (1-\\lambda )(-\\lambda )-2\\, =\\, \\lambda ^2 - \\lambda - 2 = (\\lambda -2)(\\lambda +1).[/mathjax]|   ---|---          The roots of [mathjaxinline]\\, P(\\lambda )\\,[/mathjaxinline] are [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline]; therefore, the eigenvalues of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] are [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline].  **Problem 8.2** Find the eigenvalues of the matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}= \\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 3 \\\\\\ 0 & 6 \\\\\\ \\end{pmatrix}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] (This matrix is called **upper triangular** because all its entries below the diagonal are zero.)    ###  Solution:  The characteristic polynomial is  [mathjax]\\mathrm{det}(\\mathbf{A}-\\lambda \\mathbf{I}) = \\mathrm{det}\\begin{pmatrix} 2-\\lambda & 3 \\\\\\ 0 & 6-\\lambda \\end{pmatrix} = (\\lambda -2)(\\lambda -6),[/mathjax]|   ---|---      so the eigenvalues are [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]6[/mathjaxinline].     **Remark:** In general, the eigenvalues of an upper (or lower) triangular matrix are simply its diagonal entries.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Finding eigenvalues", "filename": "13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab8-text1.html", "title": "Finding eigenvalues"}

{"pageid": 45, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab3", "text": "Recall that for a first order homogeneous linear ODE with constant coefficients [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{x}-kx=0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] the general solution is the exponential [mathjaxinline]\\, x=Ce^{kt}.[/mathjaxinline] For higher order equations [mathjaxinline]\\, P(D) x =0[/mathjaxinline], we made the **ansatz** (an educated guess) that solutions take the form [mathjaxinline]\\, x(t)=e^{\\lambda t}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] This trial solution led us to the characteristic equation [mathjaxinline]\\, P(\\lambda )=0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] which led, in turn, to all solutions.    We want to do the same for systems. Let us start with the easiest kind of 2 by 2 systems, namely an uncoupled system.  **An uncoupled 2 by 2 system**    What is the general solution to the system  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} \\dot{x}\\\\\\ \\dot{y} \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 3 \\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix} x\\\\\\ y \\end{pmatrix} ?[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Solution:**    This system decomposes into two equations, each with only one dependent variable:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 2x[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.57)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 3y.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.58)      We know how to solve each of the two equations separately:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_1 e^{2t}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.59)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_2 e^{3t}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.60)      where [mathjaxinline]c_1,c_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] are arbitrary constants. In vector notation, this is  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} x \\\\\\ y \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} c_1e ^{2t} \\\\\\ c_2 e^{3t} \\end{pmatrix} =c_1\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}e^{2t} + c_2 \\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}e^{3t}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  The exponential ansatz", "filename": "13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab3-text1.html", "title": "The exponential ansatz"}

To get an accurate understanding of the pendulum when [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline] is not always small, we need to analyze the differential equation  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ddot{\\theta } +b\\dot{\\theta } + g \\sin \\theta[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.6)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      in its full non-linear glory. It is a **second-order non-linear ODE,** which we have not developed tools for.    To tackle it, we start by converting the single ODE to its companion system by defining a new variable [mathjaxinline]\\omega = \\dot{\\theta },\\,[/mathjaxinline] the angular velocity of the mass:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\theta }[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\omega[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\omega }[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -b\\omega - g \\sin \\theta .[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The companion system is a **first order non-linear system** of the form  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\theta }[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f\\left(\\theta ,\\omega \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\omega }[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle h\\left(\\theta ,\\omega \\right).[/mathjaxinline] |  |      It is **autonomous** because the right hand sides of both equations do not depend on time explicitly.  For general non-linear equations, converting to a first order companion system is often a good first step to take. This is what many numerical differential equation solvers do. {"pageid": 48, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab9", "text": "### Finding the eigenvectors associated to an eigenvalue  The next step in solving the system [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x},\\,[/mathjaxinline] is to find the eigenvectors associated with each eigenvalue of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline]  An **eigenvector associated with an eigenvalue** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\lambda }}[/mathjaxinline] is a **nonzero** solution to the linear system below:  [mathjax]\\left(\\mathbf{A}- \\lambda \\mathbf{I}\\right) \\mathbf v= \\mathbf{0}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      There is always a nonzero solution for [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v\\,[/mathjaxinline] because by definition [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline] is such that [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathrm{det}\\left(\\mathbf{A}- \\lambda \\mathbf{I}\\right) =0.\\,[/mathjaxinline]  **Example 9.1** Recall from the previous page that the matrix  [mathjax]\\mathbf{A}= \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & -2 \\\\\\ -1 & 0 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      has eigenvalues [mathjaxinline]\\, 2 \\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, -1.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] What are the eigenvectors associated to each of the eigenvalues?  **Solution:**   **For the eigenvalue** [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda _1=2[/mathjaxinline] **:**    [mathjax]\\mathbf{A}-\\lambda _1 \\mathbf{I}=\\mathbf{A}- 2 \\mathbf{I}= \\begin{pmatrix} 1 -2 & -2 \\\\\\ -1 & 0-2 \\end{pmatrix}= \\begin{pmatrix} -1 & -2 \\\\\\ -1 & -2 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Therefore, we need to solve the system  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} -1 & -2 \\\\\\ -1 & -2 \\end{pmatrix} \\mathbf v_1 = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Writing [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v_1=\\begin{pmatrix} a_1 \\\\\\ a_2 \\end{pmatrix},\\,[/mathjaxinline] the vector equation above can be rewritten as  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} -1 & -2 \\\\\\ -1 & -2 \\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix} a_1 \\\\\\ a_2 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Note that we only need to solve the single equation  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle -a_1-2a_2=0.[/mathjaxinline] | | (2.76)   ---|---|---|---      (If the two equations are **not** redundant, you have made a mistake!)    By inspection, [mathjaxinline]\\, a_1=2,\\,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]a_2=-1[/mathjaxinline] (or any multiple of this pair) works.  Therefore, the eigenvectors of the eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]\\lambda =2[/mathjaxinline] are all scalar multiples of  [mathjax]\\mathbf v_1 = \\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\\\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **For the eigenvalue** [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda _2=-1[/mathjaxinline] **:**    [mathjax]\\mathbf{A}- \\lambda _2 \\mathbf{I}= A- (-1) \\mathbf{I}=\\begin{pmatrix} 1-(-1) & -2 \\\\\\ -1 & 0-(-1) \\end{pmatrix}= \\begin{pmatrix} 2 & -2 \\\\\\ -1 & 1 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Therefore, we need to solve the linear system  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} 2 & -2 \\\\\\ -1 & 1 \\end{pmatrix} \\mathbf v_2 = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Let [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v_2=\\begin{pmatrix} b_1 \\\\\\ b_2 \\end{pmatrix}.\\,[/mathjaxinline] The vector equation above is equivalent to the single equation  [mathjax]b_1=b_2.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Therefore, all eigenvectors of the eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline] are scalar multiples of  [mathjax]\\mathbf v_2 = \\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Summary:**   The matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}= \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & -2 \\\\\\ -1 & 0 \\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline] has two eigenvalues-eigenvector pairs:    * [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda _1 = 2, \\,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v_1=\\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\\\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix}, \\,[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda _2 = -1, \\,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v_2=\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline].   Finding the eigenvectors of an eigenvalue", "filename": "13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab9-text2.html", "title": "Finding the eigenvectors of an eigenvalue"}

{"pageid": 49, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@limitcycles/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@limitcycles-tab2", "text": "Given a 2x2 autonomous system of differential equations  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(x,y)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.202)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle h(x,y),[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.203)      write [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{F}= \\begin{pmatrix} f(x,y) \\\\\\ h(x,y) \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] for the vector field defined by this system.  ### The Poincar\u00e9\u2013Bendixson Theorem  Suppose that [mathjaxinline]R[/mathjaxinline] is a finite region of the plane bounded between two simple closed curves [mathjaxinline]C_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]C_2[/mathjaxinline]. If    1. at each point of [mathjaxinline]C_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]C_2[/mathjaxinline] the field [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{F}[/mathjaxinline] points towards the interior of [mathjaxinline]R[/mathjaxinline], and     2. [mathjaxinline]R[/mathjaxinline] contains no critical points,   then the system has a closed trajectory lying inside [mathjaxinline]R[/mathjaxinline].  ### Bendixson's Thereom  Let [mathjaxinline]D[/mathjaxinline] be a region in the plane. If [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{div} \\mathbf{F}[/mathjaxinline] is never zero in [mathjaxinline]D[/mathjaxinline], then there are no closed trajectories in [mathjaxinline]D[/mathjaxinline]. (In particular, there can be no limit cycles.)  The theorem", "filename": "limitcycles-tab2-text1.html", "title": "The theorem"}

[mathjaxinline]\\, Y\\,[/mathjaxinline] to approximate the deviations from the critical point so that [mathjaxinline]X \\approx x-1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]Y \\approx y-2,\\,[/mathjaxinline] we have the linearized system  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} \\dot{X} \\\\\\ \\dot{Y} \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} -1 & -1 \\\\\\ 2 & -2 \\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} X \\\\\\ Y \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.119)   ---|---|---|---      The matrix has trace [mathjaxinline]-3[/mathjaxinline] and determinant [mathjaxinline]4[/mathjaxinline], so the characteristic polynomial is [mathjaxinline]\\lambda ^2 + 3\\lambda + 4[/mathjaxinline], and the eigenvalues are [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{-3 \\pm \\sqrt{-7}}{2}[/mathjaxinline]. These are complex numbers with negative real part, so this describes a spiral sink.  ###  Alternate solution by change of variables  To understand the deer-wolf system near the critical point [mathjaxinline](1,2)[/mathjaxinline], reduce to the previously solved case of [mathjaxinline](0,0)[/mathjaxinline] by making the change of variable  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 1 + X[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 2 + Y[/mathjaxinline] |  |      so that [mathjaxinline](x,y)=(1,2)[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline](X,Y)=(0,0)[/mathjaxinline] in the new coordinate system. Then  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{X} = \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 3(1+X)-(1+X)^2 -(1+X)(2+Y) = -X - Y - X^2 - XY \\approx -X - Y[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{Y} = \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\quad (2+Y)-(2+Y)^2+(1+X)(2+Y) = 2X - 2Y - Y^2 + XY \\approx 2X - 2Y[/mathjaxinline] |  |      when [mathjaxinline](X,Y)[/mathjaxinline] is close to [mathjaxinline](0,0)[/mathjaxinline]. In matrix form,  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} \\dot{X} \\\\\\ \\dot{Y} \\end{pmatrix} \\approx \\begin{pmatrix} -1 & -1 \\\\\\ 2 & -2 \\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix} X \\\\\\ Y \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Remark:** We are using the variables [mathjaxinline]\\, X\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, Y\\,[/mathjaxinline] in the two solutions in different ways. In the previous solution, [mathjaxinline]\\, X\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, Y\\,[/mathjaxinline] approximate the deviations [mathjaxinline]\\, x-1\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, y-2,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and therefore the linearized system is written with an equal sign. In this alternate solution, [mathjaxinline]\\, X\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, Y\\,[/mathjaxinline] equal the deviations, and hence the linearized system is written with an approximation sign. {"pageid": 57, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@15_stability/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@15_stability-tab10", "text": "**Full picture of trace determinant plane**  ![The trace determinant plane is has horizontal axis Tr, the vertical axis Det, and the critical parabola Det equals Tr squared over 4, breaking the plane into six regions. Spiral sinks are above the critical parabola and to the left of the vertical axis in the second quadrant. Spiral sources are above the critical parabola and to the right of the vertical Det axis in the first quadrant. The positive Det axis are centers. Nodal sinks are above the horizontal Tr axis, below the critical parabola, and to the left of the vertical Det axis in the second quadrant. Nodal sources are above the horizontal Tr axis, below the critical parabola, and to the right of the vertical Det axis in the first quadrant. The critical parabola is degenerate nodes and stars. The horizontal Tr axis minus the origin is combs. The region below the horizontal Tr axis is saddles.](/static/images/u3s4_tdfull.svg)  The **trace-determinant plane** is the plane with axes [mathjaxinline]\\text{Tr}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\text{Det}[/mathjaxinline]. This is completely different from the phase plane (the axes are different).  Whereas the phase portrait shows all possible trajectories for a system [mathjaxinline]\\dot{\\mathbf{x}}=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x},\\,[/mathjaxinline] for a specific [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline], the trace-determinant plane has just one point for that system. The position of that point contains information about the kind of phase portrait describing the system.  Above the critical parabola [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\text{Det} =\\frac{ \\text{Tr}^2}{4},\\,[/mathjaxinline] the eigenvalues are complex. {"pageid": 62, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@12_motivationforsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@12_motivationforsystems-tab3", "text": "### Scalar multiplication  Multiplying a vector by a scalar, which is a real number, means multiply each component of the vector by that number.     **Scalar multiplication example:** [mathjaxinline]\\quad \\displaystyle 3\\begin{pmatrix} -2\\\\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix} =\\begin{pmatrix} -6 \\\\\\ -3 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline]  Geometrically, multiplication of a vector by a positive scalar changes the length of the vector by the corresponding factor without changing its direction.  ![See caption](/static/images/u3s1_scalarmult.svg)    **Figure 4** : [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 3{\\color{blue}{\\begin{pmatrix} -2\\\\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix}}} ={\\color{orange}{\\begin{pmatrix} -6 \\\\\\ -3 \\end{pmatrix}}} .[/mathjaxinline]   The 2 vectors lie on the same line but the length   of [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{\\begin{pmatrix} -6 \\\\\\ -3 \\end{pmatrix}}}[/mathjaxinline] is 3 times the length of [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\begin{pmatrix} -2\\\\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix}}}[/mathjaxinline].  Multiplying a vector by any negative scalar changes the direction of the vector\u2013 it lies along the same line, but points in the opposite direction.  ![See caption](/static/images/u3s1_scalarmultneg.svg)    **Figure 5** : [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (-3) {\\color{blue}{\\begin{pmatrix} -2\\\\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix}}} ={\\color{orange}{\\begin{pmatrix} 6 \\\\\\ 3 \\end{pmatrix}}} .[/mathjaxinline]   The 2 vectors lie on the same line but [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{\\begin{pmatrix} 6 \\\\\\ 3 \\end{pmatrix}}}[/mathjaxinline] points in the opposite direction of [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\begin{pmatrix} -2\\\\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix}}}[/mathjaxinline].  The set of all scalar multiples of a single vector form the line through origin that the vector lies on; the set of all positive scalar multiples of a single vector form a ray starting at the origin through the vector.  ![See caption](/static/images/u3s1_scalarmultray.svg)    **Figure 6** : [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c {\\color{blue}{\\begin{pmatrix} -2\\\\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix}}} ={\\color{orange}{\\begin{pmatrix} -2c \\\\\\ -c \\end{pmatrix}}}[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]c=1,\\, 2,\\, 3,\\, 4[/mathjaxinline]   The set of all vectors [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{\\begin{pmatrix} -2c \\\\\\ -c \\end{pmatrix}}}[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]c>0[/mathjaxinline] form a ray in the same direction as [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\begin{pmatrix} -2\\\\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix}}}[/mathjaxinline]  ![See caption](/static/images/u3s1_scalarmultline.svg)     **Figure 7** : [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c {\\color{blue}{\\begin{pmatrix} -2\\\\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix}}} ={\\color{orange}{\\begin{pmatrix} -2c \\\\\\ -c \\end{pmatrix}}}[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]c=\\pm 1,\\, \\pm 2,\\, \\pm 3,\\, \\pm 4[/mathjaxinline]   The set of all vectors [mathjaxinline]{\\color{orange}{\\begin{pmatrix} -2c \\\\\\ -c \\end{pmatrix}}}[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] any real number form a line through [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\begin{pmatrix} -2\\\\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix}}}[/mathjaxinline]   **Linear independence and basis in the plane**  We have discussed linear independence, linear combination, and bases in higher dimensions in the last course _Introduction to differential equations_. Since we will only deal with 2 dimensions in this course, we review these notions for 2 dimensions here.  Two vectors are **linearly dependent** if they lie on the same line. Algebraically, one vector is a multiple of the other vector.  In [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^2[/mathjaxinline], two nonzero vectors are **linearly independent** if they do not lie on the same line through the origin.  ###  N independent vectors  A set of [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] vectors being linearly independent means that there is no [mathjaxinline](n-1)[/mathjaxinline]-dimensional plane through the origin on which they all lie. To recognize this independence property algebraically for [mathjaxinline]n>2[/mathjaxinline] is more complicated. We defined linear independence in general in lecture 8 of _Introduction to differential equations_. We will discuss the higher dimensional case in the next course _Linear algebra and systems of differential equations_.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Example 3.1**    1. In the previous example,   [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} -3 \\\\\\ -6 \\end{pmatrix} = -3\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 2\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      thus the vectors [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} -3 \\\\\\ -6 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 2\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] are linearly dependent.    2. In particular, the zero vector [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] is dependent on all vectors since   [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix} = 0\\begin{pmatrix} a \\\\\\ b\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for any real numbers [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] an [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline].  **Example 3.2**  ![Two blue vectors point from the origin along a line in opposite directions. An orange vector points from the origin to a point not along the same line.](/static/images/basisR2.svg)     **Figure 8** : The pair of blue vectors is **linearly dependent**.   Any pair of 1 orange vector and 1 blue vector is **linearly independent**.   **Definition 3.3** A **linear combination** of vectors [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_2[/mathjaxinline] is a sum  [mathjax]c_1\\mathbf v_1+c_2\\mathbf v_2[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]c_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]c_2[/mathjaxinline] are scalars.  **Example 3.4** The **standard basis** of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^2[/mathjaxinline] is the pair of vectors  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}, \\quad \\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Every vector in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^2[/mathjaxinline] can be expressed as a linear combination of these vectors:  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} a\\\\\\ b \\end{pmatrix} = a\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix} + b \\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Every pair of linearly independent vectors in [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^2[/mathjaxinline] is a **basis** of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbb {R}^2[/mathjaxinline].  Scalar multiplication", "filename": "12_motivationforsystems-tab3-text4.html", "title": "Scalar multiplication"}

{"pageid": 63, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@14_phaseportraits/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@14_phaseportraits-tab9", "text": "When the coefficient matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] of the system [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}\\,[/mathjaxinline] has complex eigenvalues, we will need to perform an extra step to extract the real solutions, similar to what we did for single second order ODEs with complex characteristic roots.  Recall again the companion system of a damped oscillator with unit mass  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dt}\\begin{pmatrix} x\\\\\\ y\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\\\\\ -k & -b\\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} x\\\\\\ y\\end{pmatrix}\\qquad (y= \\dot{x}).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.22)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      We will now consider the case when the oscillator is **underdamped** [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\left(b^2-4k<0\\right),\\,[/mathjaxinline] and the eigenvalues are **complex**. We will start with the undamped case, that is, [mathjaxinline]\\, b=0[/mathjaxinline].     **Simple harmonic oscillator: [mathjaxinline]b=0[/mathjaxinline]**    In the case when an oscillator is undamped [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\left(b=0\\right),\\,[/mathjaxinline] the characteristic polynomial is [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathrm{det}(\\mathbf{A}-\\lambda \\mathbf{I})=\\begin{vmatrix} -\\lambda & 1 \\\\\\ -k & -\\lambda \\end{vmatrix} =\\lambda ^2+k,\\,[/mathjaxinline] so the eigenvalues are purely imaginary:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\, \\lambda _1\\, =\\, i\\omega ,\\, \\qquad \\lambda _2\\, =\\, -i\\omega \\qquad \\text{where }\\, \\omega =\\sqrt{k}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.23)   ---|---|---|---      The eigenvalues are complex conjugates of one another [mathjaxinline]\\, (\\lambda _1 =\\overline{\\lambda _2})\\,[/mathjaxinline] because they are the roots of a quadratic polynomial. Because this is a companion system, the corresponding eigenvectors are  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\, \\mathbf v_1\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ i\\omega \\end{pmatrix}\\, ,\\, \\qquad \\mathbf v_2\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ - i\\omega \\end{pmatrix},[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.24)   ---|---|---|---      which are again complex conjugates of one another. These then yield a pair of exponential solutions [mathjaxinline]\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ i\\omega \\end{pmatrix}e^{i\\omega t},\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ -i\\omega \\end{pmatrix}e^{-i\\omega t},\\,[/mathjaxinline] which are also complex conjugates of one another.  The general solution to the system is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} x\\\\\\ y\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_1 \\, \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ i\\omega \\end{pmatrix}e^{ i\\omega t}+ c_2\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ - i\\omega \\end{pmatrix}e^{- i\\omega t}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.25)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      This general solution is complex. Physical quantities are real valued functions and so we are interested in the real solutions to this system. These will give the position and velocity of the oscillating mass.  **Question 9.1** What are the real solutions to this system?  **Solution:**    A real solution to the system is any linear combination of the real and imaginary parts of the exponential solution [mathjaxinline]\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ i\\omega \\end{pmatrix}e^{ i\\omega t}.\\,[/mathjaxinline] To find the real and imaginary parts, we use Euler's formula  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{i \\omega t}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\cos \\left(\\omega t\\right)+i\\sin \\left(\\omega t\\right),[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.26)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      and decompose the exponential solution into its real and imaginary parts:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ i\\omega \\end{pmatrix}e^{ i\\omega t}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ i\\omega \\end{pmatrix} \\left( \\cos \\left(\\omega t\\right)+i\\sin \\left(\\omega t\\right) \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.27)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} \\cos (\\omega t) \\\\\\ -\\omega \\sin \\left(\\omega t\\right) \\end{pmatrix} + i \\begin{pmatrix} \\sin (\\omega t)\\\\\\ \\omega \\cos (\\omega t) \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.28)      The general real solution is the family of all linear combinations of the real and imaginary parts of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ i\\omega \\end{pmatrix}e^{ i\\omega t}[/mathjaxinline] with real coefficients:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\mathbf{x}(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle C_1\\mathrm{Re\\, }\\left[ \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ i\\omega \\end{pmatrix}e^{ i\\omega t}\\right] +C_2 \\mathrm{Im\\, }\\left[\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ i\\omega \\end{pmatrix}e^{ i\\omega t}\\right][/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.29)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle C_1 \\begin{pmatrix} \\cos (\\omega t) \\\\\\ -\\omega \\sin (\\omega t) \\end{pmatrix} +C_2\\begin{pmatrix} \\sin (\\omega t) \\\\\\ \\omega \\cos (\\omega t) \\end{pmatrix}\\qquad \\left(C_1,C_2 \\, \\text{real}\\right).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.30)      We could have equivalently taken the real and imaginary parts of the other exponential solution [mathjaxinline]\\, e^{ -i\\omega t}\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ -i\\omega \\end{pmatrix},\\,[/mathjaxinline] since it is the complex conjugate of the exponential solution [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf e^{i\\omega t}\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ i\\omega \\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline] used above.  ###  Justification:      The following argument why the above strategy gives the real solution. The general complex solution of the system is of the form  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle c_1 \\, \\mathbf{x}_1+c_2 \\mathbf{x}_2\\qquad \\text{where }\\, \\mathbf{x}_1 =\\overline{\\mathbf{x}_2}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.31)   ---|---|---|---      For our system [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{x}_1= \\mathbf v_1 e^{ \\lambda _1 t}=\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ i\\omega \\end{pmatrix}e^{ i\\omega t},\\,[/mathjaxinline] but we will see that exactly what [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{x}_1\\,[/mathjaxinline] is does not matter. What matters is that the general solution is a linear combination of two (vector-valued) functions that are complex conjugates of one another.   For any complex expression to be real, it must equal its complex conjugates. Therefore, the general real solution must satisfy  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle c_1 \\, \\mathbf{x}_1+c_2 \\mathbf{x}_2[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\overline{c_1 \\, \\mathbf{x}_1+c_2 \\mathbf{x}_2}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.32)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\overline{c_1}\\mathbf{x}_2+\\overline{c_2}\\mathbf{x}_1\\qquad \\left(\\text{using }\\, \\mathbf{x}_1=\\overline{\\mathbf{x}_2}\\right).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.33)      Because [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{x}_1\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{x}_2[/mathjaxinline] are linearly independent functions, the equation above implies  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle c_1=\\overline{c_2}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.34)   ---|---|---|---      The general real solution is then  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle c_1 \\, \\mathbf{x}_1+\\overline{c_1} \\overline{\\mathbf{x}_1} \\, \\qquad (\\text{where }\\, c_1 \\, \\text{is any complex number}).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.35)   ---|---|---|---      Let us rewrite this as linear combinations of real functions. Let [mathjaxinline]\\, c_1=a+bi\\,[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]a,\\, b\\,[/mathjaxinline] are any real numbers. We have  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle c_1 \\, \\mathbf{x}_1+\\overline{c_1} \\overline{\\mathbf{x}_1} \\,[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (a+bi) \\mathbf{x}_1+(a-bi) \\overline{\\mathbf{x}_1}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.36)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle a\\left(\\mathbf{x}_1+\\overline{\\mathbf{x}_1}\\right) + b i \\left(\\mathbf{x}_1-\\overline{\\mathbf{x}_1}\\right)\\qquad (\\text{regrouping})[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.37)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle a\\left(2\\mathrm{Re\\, }[\\mathbf{x}_1]\\right) + b\\left(-2 \\mathrm{Im\\, }[\\mathbf{x}_1]\\right).\\qquad (a,b\\, \\, \\text{arbitrary real constants}).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.38)      This is exactly the same as the solution we had before: any real linear combination of the real and imaginary parts of either exponential solution.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Question 9.2** What do the trajectories of the real solutions look like on the phase plane?  **Solution:**    Consider the special case with [mathjaxinline]\\, C_1=1,\\,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]\\, C_2=0[/mathjaxinline]:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\mathbf{x}(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} \\cos (\\omega t) \\\\\\ -\\omega \\sin (\\omega t) \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.39)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      This is very similar to the parametrization [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} \\cos (\\omega t) \\\\\\ \\sin (\\omega t) \\end{pmatrix} \\,[/mathjaxinline] of a circle centered at the origin, except with the [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]- and [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]- axes stretched by different amounts. Therefore, the trajectory of this solution is an ellipse centered at the origin. The **period** of the trajectory, the time it takes to trace out one complete ellipse, is [mathjaxinline]\\, 2\\pi /\\omega .[/mathjaxinline]    Another way to see that [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{x}(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] parametrizes an ellipse is that the two components of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{x}(t)=\\begin{pmatrix} x(t)\\\\\\ y(t) \\end{pmatrix}\\, = \\begin{pmatrix} \\cos (\\omega t) \\\\\\ -\\omega \\sin (\\omega t) \\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline] satisfy the equation  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle x(t)^2+\\left(\\frac{y(t)}{\\omega }\\right)^2=1\\qquad \\text{for all }\\, t.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.40)   ---|---|---|---      The trajectories of all other real solutions are also ellipses centered at the origins with the same period [mathjaxinline]\\, 2\\pi /\\omega[/mathjaxinline].    ###  How do we see that the other trajectories are also ellipses?  One way to see this is by rewriting each component of the general real solution in amplitude-phase form (introduced in the course _Introduction to differential equations_ ):  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\mathbf{x}(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_1\\begin{pmatrix} \\cos (\\omega t) \\\\\\ -\\omega \\sin (\\omega t) \\end{pmatrix} +c_2\\begin{pmatrix} \\sin (\\omega t) \\\\\\ \\omega \\cos (\\omega t) \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.41)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} c_1\\cos (\\omega t)+ c_2\\sin (\\omega t) \\\\\\ \\omega \\left(- c_1\\sin (\\omega t)+c_2\\cos (\\omega t) \\right)\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.42)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} A\\cos (\\omega t-\\phi ) \\\\\\ -\\omega A\\sin (\\omega t-\\phi ) \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.43)      where the real numbers [mathjaxinline]\\, A\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\phi \\,[/mathjaxinline] are the amplitude and phase lag of the sinusoid [mathjaxinline]\\, c_1\\cos (\\omega t)+ c_2\\sin (\\omega t).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Note that the second component of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{x}(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is the derivative of the first component since [mathjaxinline]\\, y=\\dot{x}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] The trajectory of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}(t)[/mathjaxinline] is an ellipse centered at the origin. The amplitude [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline] and angular frequency [mathjaxinline]\\, \\omega \\,[/mathjaxinline] scales the size of the ellipse, the angular frequency [mathjaxinline]\\, \\omega \\,[/mathjaxinline] determines how much the ellipse differs from the circle, and the phase lag [mathjaxinline]\\phi[/mathjaxinline] determines the location of the point [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}(0)[/mathjaxinline] on the ellipse.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Here is the phase portrait of this system when the spring constant [mathjaxinline]k=2[/mathjaxinline]:  ![See caption](/static/images/u3s3_centertall.svg)    **Figure 15** : Trajectories are ellipses centered at the origin. The ellipses are tall since for this value of [mathjaxinline]k,\\,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]\\, \\omega =\\sqrt{k}>1[/mathjaxinline].   (How would the shape of the ellipses change if we choose [mathjaxinline]\\, k=1/4[/mathjaxinline] instead?) {"pageid": 65, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab10", "text": "**Fact 1.** Eigenvectors associated with different eigenvalues are linearly independent.  **Example 10.1** In the previous example where [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}= \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & -2 \\\\\\ -1 & 0 \\end{pmatrix},\\,[/mathjaxinline] the eigenvector [mathjaxinline]\\, \\begin{pmatrix} -2 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix} \\,[/mathjaxinline] associated with the eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]\\, 2, \\,[/mathjaxinline] and the eigenvector [mathjaxinline]\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] associated with the eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]\\, -1\\,[/mathjaxinline] are linearly independent. Geometrically, these two eigenvectors do not lie on the same line.  ###  Proof  We will show that two eigenvectors associated to different eigenvalues to an [mathjaxinline]\\, N\\times N\\,[/mathjaxinline] matrix are linearly independent. We will show that if we assume the eigenvectors are dependent, a contradiction will arise.    Consider [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v_1\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v_2[/mathjaxinline] be eigenvectors associated to 2 **distinct** eigenvalues [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _1\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda _2[/mathjaxinline] respectively. If [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v_1\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v_2[/mathjaxinline] are linearly dependent, then  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf v_1=c\\mathbf v_2 \\qquad \\text{for some scalar }\\, c.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.84)   ---|---|---|---      First writing [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_1[/mathjaxinline] in terms of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v_2[/mathjaxinline] then applying [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] gives  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf v_1=\\mathbf{A}\\left(c\\mathbf v_2\\right)= c\\left(\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf v_2\\right)= c\\left(\\lambda _2 \\mathbf v_2\\right)= \\lambda _2 (c\\mathbf v_2)=\\lambda _2 \\mathbf v_1.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.85)   ---|---|---|---      At the same time, applying the matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v_1[/mathjaxinline] directly gives  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf v_1=\\lambda _1 \\mathbf v_1.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.86)   ---|---|---|---      This means  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda _1 \\mathbf v_1=\\lambda _2 \\mathbf v_1[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longleftrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(\\lambda _1-\\lambda _2\\right) \\mathbf v_1=\\mathbf{0}.[/mathjaxinline] | | (2.87)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Since [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v_1[/mathjaxinline] is nonzero, [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _1=\\lambda _2.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] This is impossible since we started with [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda _1\\neq \\lambda _2[/mathjaxinline]! Hence, the premise that [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v_2[/mathjaxinline] are linearly dependent must be false, and so they must be linearly **independent**.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  As a consequence of Fact 1, we have:  **Fact 2.** If a [mathjaxinline]2 \\times 2[/mathjaxinline] matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] has two **distinct** eigenvalues, then any pair of eigenvectors corresponding to the two eigenvalues form a basis of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbb {R}^2[/mathjaxinline].  This is because no matter how we choose the two eigenvectors, they are linearly independent by Fact 1, and so they form a basis.     **Remark:**   When finding the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of the matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}= \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & -2 \\\\\\ -1 & 0\\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline] in the previous example, we gave only one eigenvector associated to each eigenvalue. It does not matter which eigenvector we pick for each eigenvalue. For example, we could have given the eigenvalue-eigenvector pairs:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\mathbf v_1=\\begin{pmatrix} 2\\\\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix}\\qquad \\text{ for } \\lambda _1=2[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.88)   ---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf v_2=\\begin{pmatrix} 7\\\\\\ 7 \\end{pmatrix}\\qquad \\text{ for } \\lambda _2=-1.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.89)      However, it is redundant to choose more than one dependent eigenvectors.  Facts about eigenvectors", "filename": "13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab10-text1.html", "title": "Facts about eigenvectors"}

This means that **far away from the origin** , trajectories become parallel to the eigenline corresponding to the smaller, more negative, eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda _1.[/mathjaxinline]    Here is a sketch of several trajectories:  ![See caption](/static/images/u3s3_overdampedphaseportrait2.svg)    **Figure 13** : Trajectories approach the origin along the **blue** eigenline, which corresponds to the [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda _2 \\, \\, (\\lambda _1<\\lambda _2<0)[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 70, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@33_autonomoussystemsstability/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@33_autonomoussystemsstability-tab1", "text": "### Objectives  After this section and some practice, you should be able to:    * **Model two interacting populations.**    * Determine the **stability** and **structural stability** of the linearized system at a critical point using the Jacobian matrix.     * Use structural stability of a critical point to determine whether an autonomous nonlinear system behaves like its linear approximation near the critical point.     * Use **conservation of energy** to determine the phase portrait of an **undamped pendulum.**  Objectives", "filename": "33_autonomoussystemsstability-tab1-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 71, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@12_motivationforsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@12_motivationforsystems-tab7", "text": "![Two large cylindrical tanks are connected at the bottom by a very thin pipe. The height of fluid in tank 1 is h1, the height of fluid in tank 2 is h2. There is a leak in tank 2. ](/static/images/tanks2leaking_copy.svg)  How do we model the leak in the second tank? In this case, there is additional fluid flowing out of tank 2. Since the leak is at the bottom of the tank, the rate of leakage is proportional to the pressure. Pressure is proportional to the weight of fluid above the leak. The weight of fluid above the leak is proportional to the height [mathjaxinline]h_2[/mathjaxinline] of the fluid in tank 2. Therefore the rate of leakage is [mathjaxinline]\\, bh_2,\\,[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] is a positive constant of proportionality.    Therefore, the differential equation tank 2 becomes  [mathjax]\\frac{dh_2}{dt} = a(h_1-h_2)- b h_2.[/mathjax]| (2.5)   ---|---      Note that the equation for [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\frac{dh_1}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] remains unchanged,  (If the leak were higher in the tank, then the rate of leakage would be proportional to the difference between [mathjaxinline]h_2[/mathjaxinline] and the height of the leak. )  A leaking tank", "filename": "12_motivationforsystems-tab7-text1.html", "title": "A leaking tank"}

{"pageid": 72, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@14_phaseportraits/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@14_phaseportraits-tab3", "text": "**Question 3.1** How can we visualize a solution [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{x}=\\begin{pmatrix} x(t)\\\\\\ y(t) \\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\dot{\\mathbf{x}} = \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline] for a constant [mathjaxinline]2 \\times 2[/mathjaxinline] real matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline]?  **Answer:**   Make two plots, the first showing [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] as a function of [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline], and the second showing [mathjaxinline]y(t)[/mathjaxinline] as a function of [mathjaxinline]t.[/mathjaxinline]  **Better answer:**   Draw the solution as a parametrized curve on the [mathjaxinline](x,y)[/mathjaxinline]-plane. In other words, plot the point [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left( x(t),\\, y(t)\\right)\\,[/mathjaxinline] for every real number [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] (including negative [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline]). The differential equation [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{\\mathbf{x}} = \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x},\\,[/mathjaxinline] specifies which direction the point [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left( x(t),\\, y(t)\\right)\\,[/mathjaxinline] will move next (and how fast), in terms of its current position.    **Warm up: trajectory of** [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{orange}{\\mathbf ve^{\\lambda t}}}[/mathjaxinline]    Recall that if [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] is an eigenvector associated to a real eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda \\,[/mathjaxinline] of a matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf ve^{\\lambda t}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a solution to [mathjaxinline]\\dot{\\mathbf{x}} = \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Sketch the trajectory of such a solution on the [mathjaxinline](x,y)[/mathjaxinline]-plane.  **Solution:**    Since [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda \\,[/mathjaxinline] is real, [mathjaxinline]\\, e^{\\lambda t}>0\\,[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]\\, t.\\,[/mathjaxinline] Therefore each point of the solution [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf ve^{\\lambda t}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a positive scalar multiple of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] This means the trajectory lies on the ray through the eigenvector [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] The direction of the trajectory depends on the sign of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda[/mathjaxinline] as follow:    * If [mathjaxinline]\\lambda =0[/mathjaxinline], the trajectory is a single point because [mathjaxinline]\\, \\begin{pmatrix} x(t)\\\\\\ y(t) \\end{pmatrix}=\\mathbf ve^{\\lambda t} =\\mathbf v.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] That is, the solution is stationary at the point [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] The point [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] is called a **critical point** since [mathjaxinline]\\dot{\\mathbf{x}}=\\mathbf{0}[/mathjaxinline] there.     * If [mathjaxinline]\\lambda >0[/mathjaxinline], the trajectory points towards infinity (is repelled from [mathjaxinline](0,0)[/mathjaxinline]).     * If [mathjaxinline]\\lambda <0[/mathjaxinline], the trajectory points towards [mathjaxinline](0,0)[/mathjaxinline] (is attracted to [mathjaxinline](0,0)[/mathjaxinline]).   Here are the sketches of the trajectories for the three cases:  ![Single point. See text above](/static/images/u3s3_linetrajectoryzero.svg)| ![Trajectory towards infinity. See text above](/static/images/u3s3_linetrajectorypos.svg)| ![Trajectory towards origin. See text above](/static/images/u3s3_linetrajectoryneg.svg)   ---|---|---   [mathjaxinline]\\lambda =0[/mathjaxinline]|  [mathjaxinline]\\lambda >0[/mathjaxinline]|  [mathjaxinline]\\lambda <0[/mathjaxinline]           **Remark:**. We can think of the trajectory as the footprint of the solution. It records all points on the [mathjaxinline](x,y)[/mathjaxinline]-plane that the solution [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left( x(t),\\, y(t)\\right)\\,[/mathjaxinline] reaches and in which direction. However, a trajectory does not describe a solution fully. It neither shows at what time each point is reached, nor contains information about speed. {"pageid": 74, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab12", "text": "**Dimension theorem for a homogeneous linear system of ODEs.** For any first- order homogeneous linear system of [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] ODEs in [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] unknown functions  [mathjax]\\dot{{\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{x}}} } = \\mathbf{A}(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{x}}} ,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      the set of solutions is a [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline]-dimensional vector space. (This is true even if [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] is replaced by [mathjaxinline]N[/mathjaxinline] everywhere.)  The dimension theorem is a consequence of the existence and uniqueness theorem:     **Existence and uniqueness theorem for a linear system of ODEs.** Let [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}(t)[/mathjaxinline] be a square matrix-valued function and let [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{r}(t)\\,[/mathjaxinline] be a vector-valued function, both continuous on an open time interval [mathjaxinline]I[/mathjaxinline]. Let [mathjaxinline]a \\in I[/mathjaxinline], and let [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{b}[/mathjaxinline] be a vector. Then there exists a unique solution [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{x}}} (t)[/mathjaxinline] to the system  [mathjax]\\dot{{\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{x}}} } = \\mathbf{A}(t) \\, {\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{x}}} + \\mathbf{r}(t)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      satisfying the initial condition  [mathjax]{\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{x}}} (a) = \\mathbf{b}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Note that for [mathjaxinline]2\\times 2\\,[/mathjaxinline] systems, the initial condition really consists of [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] conditions, one for each component of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\begin{pmatrix} x_1(a)\\\\\\ x_2(a)\\end{pmatrix}\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} b_1\\\\\\ b_2\\end{pmatrix}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline]  In other words, to pin down one solution to a first order linear system, we need to specify the initial condition [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{x}}} (a) = \\mathbf{b},\\,[/mathjaxinline] which consists of 2 equations, one for each component, for [mathjaxinline]\\, 2\\times 2\\,[/mathjaxinline] systems.     **How does the second theorem lead to the first?**    First, set [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{r}(t)=\\mathbf{0}[/mathjaxinline] for a homogenous system. Secondly, by the existence and uniqueness theorem, once the starting time [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] is fixed, the solutions to the system are in 1-to-1 correspondence to the possibilities for the initial condition vector [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{b}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Therefore, the set of solutions to the homogeneous system is [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline]-dimensional.  In the case we have discussed so far, where [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}(t)=\\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a constant matrix with real distinct eigenvalues, and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{r}(t)=\\mathbf{0},\\,[/mathjaxinline] the general solution takes the form  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{x}(t)= \\begin{pmatrix} x(t) \\\\\\ y(t) \\end{pmatrix} = c_1 \\mathbf v_1 e^{\\lambda _1 t} + c_2 \\mathbf v_2 e^{\\lambda _2 t}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.97)   ---|---|---|---      This is consistent with the dimension theorem, because this is a two- dimensional family of solutions.  Theory of 2 by 2 systems", "filename": "13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab12-text1.html", "title": "Theory of 2 by 2 systems"}
