{"pageid": 77, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@12_motivationforsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@12_motivationforsystems-tab5", "text": "To write a system of linear DEs into a vector equation, we still need another ingredient: matrices.  A [mathjaxinline]2\\times 2[/mathjaxinline] matrix with real number entries is a table of numbers with [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] rows and [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] columns.  **Example 5.1** The following is a [mathjaxinline]2\\times 2[/mathjaxinline] matrix.  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} 1 & -8 \\\\\\ -4 & 7 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Product of a row and a column**    Multiplication of matrices is built out of one operation: the multiplication of a row with a column.  **Example 5.2**  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} {\\color{orange}{3}} & {\\color{orange}{2}} \\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix} x \\\\\\ y \\end{pmatrix} = {\\color{orange}{3}} x+{\\color{orange}{2}} y.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      We see that the product is a single number, which is the sum of the products of the respective components of the two vectors.  **Product of a matrix and a column vector**  Now with 2 rows forming a matrix, we carry out the multiplication with a column vector by multiplying each row of the matrix separately with the column vector.  **Example 5.3**  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} {\\color{blue}{3}} & {\\color{blue}{2}} \\\\\\ {\\color{orange}{5}} & {\\color{orange}{-1}} \\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix} x \\\\\\ y \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} {\\color{blue}{3}} x+{\\color{blue}{2}} y \\\\\\ {\\color{orange}{5}} x+{\\color{orange}{(-1)}} y \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This product is a column vector whose **first** entry is the product of the **first** row of the matrix with the column vector, and whose **second** entry is the product of the **second** row of the matrix with the column vector.    ###  General matrix multiplication  We have just learned how to multiply a row vector by a column vector and a matrix by a column vector. In general, two matrices can be multiplied if the number of columns of the first one is equal to the number of rows of the second one. In other words, you can only multiply an [mathjaxinline]\\, m \\times n\\,[/mathjaxinline] matrix with an [mathjaxinline]\\, n \\times p\\,[/mathjaxinline] matrix. The product is an [mathjaxinline]\\, m \\times p\\,[/mathjaxinline] matrix.  Let us illustrate again by example.  **Example 5.4** Multiply a [mathjaxinline]2 \\times 3[/mathjaxinline] matrix with a [mathjaxinline]3 \\times 2[/mathjaxinline] a matrix.  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} {\\color{blue}{2}} & {\\color{blue}{4}} & {\\color{blue}{1}} \\\\\\ {\\color{orange}{-3}} & {\\color{orange}{5}} & {\\color{orange}{-1}} \\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix} x& u \\\\\\ y & v\\\\\\ z & w \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} {\\color{blue}{2}} x+{\\color{blue}{4}} y +{\\color{blue}{1}} z & {\\color{blue}{2}} u+{\\color{blue}{4}} v +{\\color{blue}{1}} w \\\\\\ {\\color{orange}{-3}} x +{\\color{orange}{5}} y-{\\color{orange}{1}} z & {\\color{orange}{-3}} u +{\\color{orange}{5}} v-{\\color{orange}{1}} w \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The product is a [mathjaxinline]\\, 2 \\times 2\\,[/mathjaxinline] matrix. The **[mathjaxinline]i,j-[/mathjaxinline]entry** of a matrix is the entry in the [mathjaxinline]\\, i-[/mathjaxinline]th row and [mathjaxinline]\\, j-[/mathjaxinline]th column of the matrix.    The [mathjaxinline]i,j[/mathjaxinline]-entry of the product is the product of the [mathjaxinline]\\, i-[/mathjaxinline]th row of the first matrix and the [mathjaxinline]\\, j-[/mathjaxinline]th column of the second one. For example, the [mathjaxinline]2,1[/mathjaxinline]-entry of the product is the product of the second row of the first matrix and the first column of the second matrix.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Fact about matrix multiplication**    Matrix multiplication depends on the order of the factors.    When we say a product of a matrix with a vector, we mean the product in which the matrix is the first factor and the vector is the second factor.    Matrices", "filename": "12_motivationforsystems-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Matrices"}

{"pageid": 80, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@14_phaseportraits/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@14_phaseportraits-tab15", "text": "We have found the phase portrait of the undamped harmonic oscillator by solving its companion system. But there is another way to obtain the shape of the trajectories by considering the energy.     **Total Energy**    Consider the harmonic oscillator described by [mathjaxinline]\\, m\\ddot{x} + k x = 0.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] The total energy of the mass is the sum of its kinetic energy (KE) and potential energy (PE).    The kinetic energy is [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\mathrm{KE}= \\frac{m\\dot{x}^2}{2}[/mathjaxinline].  The potential energy [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{PE}[/mathjaxinline] is a function of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline], and obtained by integrating the force along the path of the oscillating mass:  [mathjax]\\underbrace{\\mathrm{PE}(x) - \\mathrm{PE}(0)}_{{\\color{blue}{\\mathrm{change\\space in\\space } \\mathrm{PE}}} } = - \\underbrace{\\int _0^x F_{\\mathrm{spring} }(X) \\, dX}_{{\\color{orange}{\\mathrm{work\\space done\\space by\\space } F_{\\mathrm{spring} }}} } = - \\int _0^x -kX \\, dX = \\frac{kx^2}{2}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      If we declare [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{PE}=0[/mathjaxinline] at position [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{PE}(x) = \\frac{kx^2}{2}[/mathjaxinline].  Therefore, the total energy of the mass is:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle E[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{KE}+\\mathrm{PE}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.60)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{m\\dot{x}^2}{2} + \\frac{kx^2}{2}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.61)       **Conservation of energy**  How does total energy change with time? Let us find the time derivative [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{E}\\,[/mathjaxinline] of the total energy of the mass.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{E}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle m \\dot{x} \\ddot{x} + k x \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.62)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}(m \\ddot{x} + kx)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.63)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0 \\qquad \\text{since}\\quad m\\ddot{x} + kx=0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.64)      Therefore, the total energy of the mass in a simple harmonic oscillator is conserved.  **Equation of ellipse from energy conservation**    Rewrite the energy equation  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle E = \\frac{m\\dot{x}^2}{2} + \\frac{kx^2}{2}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      by letting [mathjaxinline]y=\\dot{x}\\,[/mathjaxinline] and rearranging:  [mathjax]\\frac{{\\color{orange}{x}} ^2}{2E/k} + \\frac{{\\color{orange}{y}} ^2}{2E/m} = 1.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Since energy is conserved, that is, [mathjaxinline]\\, E\\,[/mathjaxinline] is constant, the equation above gives the trajectory of [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} x\\\\\\ y\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] as an ellipse with semi-axes [mathjaxinline]\\, \\sqrt{2E/k}\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\sqrt{2E/m}[/mathjaxinline]:  ![See surrounding text](/static/images/u3s3_energyellipse.svg)  **Remark:**. Suppose we start the mass to the right of equilibrium, and then let go. Then, at [mathjaxinline]\\, t=0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] we have [mathjaxinline]x>0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\dot{x}=0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] corresponding to the **orange** point above. At the first time the mass crosses equilibrium, [mathjaxinline]\\, x=0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and it has negative velocity, [mathjaxinline]\\dot{x}<0.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] This corresponds to the **black** point above. When the mass reaches its **leftmost** point, [mathjaxinline]x<0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\dot{x}=0[/mathjaxinline] again.  Phase portrait of simple harmonic oscillator using energy", "filename": "14_phaseportraits-tab15-text1.html", "title": "Phase portrait of simple harmonic oscillator using energy"}

Conversely, given a first-order system, one can eliminate function variables to find a higher-order ODE satisfied by one of the functions. But usually it is better just to leave it as a system.  **Example 13.1** Consider the system  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 2x - y[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 5x + 7y.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Find a higher-order ODE involving only [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline].  **Solution:** Solve for [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] in the first equation ([mathjaxinline]y=2x-\\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline]) and substitute into the second equation:  [mathjax]2 \\dot{x} - \\ddot{x} = 5x + 7(2x-\\dot{x}).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This simplifies to  [mathjax]\\ddot{x} - 9 \\dot{x} + 19 x = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Converting from systems to higher order equations", "filename": "12_motivationforsystems-tab13-text1.html", "title": "Converting from systems to higher order equations"}

Recall the **energy function** is the sum of the kinetic (KE) and potential (PE) energy, whose formulas are  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle KE[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{2} mv^2\\, =\\, \\frac{1}{2} m(l\\omega )^2[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.177)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle PE[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle mgh\\, =\\, mgl (1-\\cos \\theta )[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.178)      Here, [mathjaxinline]\\, v\\,[/mathjaxinline] is the tangential component of the velocity of the mass, [mathjaxinline]\\, m\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, l\\,[/mathjaxinline] are the mass and length of the pendulum, and [mathjaxinline]\\, h\\,[/mathjaxinline] is the height of the mass from the rest position at the bottom.    Since we have set the parameters [mathjaxinline]m=l=g=1,\\,[/mathjaxinline] the energy function is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle E(\\theta ,\\omega )[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle KE+PE[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.179)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{2} \\omega ^2+ (1-\\cos \\theta ).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.180)       **Conservation of energy along trajectories**    Let us compute the time derivative of energy:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot{E}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\omega \\dot{\\omega } + (\\sin \\theta ) \\dot{\\theta }[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.181)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Along any trajectory of the frictionless system, the DEs  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\theta }[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\omega[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.182)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\omega }[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = - \\sin \\theta .[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.183)      are satisfied. Substituting these into the expression for [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{E},\\,[/mathjaxinline] we have  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot{E}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\omega \\dot{\\omega } + (\\sin \\theta ) \\dot{\\theta }[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.184)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\omega (-\\sin \\theta ) + (\\sin \\theta ) \\omega \\, =\\, 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.185)      This means that along each trajectory, [mathjaxinline]\\, E\\,[/mathjaxinline] is constant. In other words, each trajectory is contained in a **level curve** of [mathjaxinline]\\, E.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Let us discuss the different cases of the level curves.     **Energy level** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{E=0}}[/mathjaxinline] **:**  [mathjax]\\frac{1}{2} \\omega ^2 + (1-\\cos \\theta ) = 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Both terms on the left are nonnegative, so their sum can be [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline] only if both are [mathjaxinline]0.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] This happens only at [mathjaxinline]\\, (\\theta ,\\omega )=(0,0)\\,[/mathjaxinline] (and the similar points [mathjaxinline](2\\pi n, 0)\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline]).The energy level [mathjaxinline]E=0[/mathjaxinline] consists of the **stationary points** at [mathjaxinline](0,0)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline](2\\pi n, 0).[/mathjaxinline]  ![See caption](/static/images/u7s2_pendulumE0.svg)    **Figure 26** : Trajectories with [mathjaxinline]E=0[/mathjaxinline] are the **stationary points** at [mathjaxinline]\\, (2\\pi n ,0)[/mathjaxinline].       **Energy level** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{E=\\epsilon }}[/mathjaxinline] **for small** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\epsilon >0}}[/mathjaxinline] **:**  [mathjax]\\frac{1}{2} \\omega ^2 + (1-\\cos \\theta ) = \\epsilon .[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Both kinetic energy and potential energy must be small, so the height is small, leading to [mathjaxinline]\\, \\theta \\,[/mathjaxinline] being small. {"pageid": 86, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab7", "text": "### Characteristic polynomial of a matrix  Recall that [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}=e^{\\lambda t} \\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] is a solution of the system of DE [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}= \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}\\,[/mathjaxinline] if and only if [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf v=\\lambda \\mathbf v,\\,[/mathjaxinline] which is equivalent to [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left(\\lambda \\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}\\right)\\mathbf v=\\mathbf{0}.[/mathjaxinline]     **Question 7.1** For what values of the parameter [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline] does the linear algebra system [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\left(\\lambda \\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}\\right) \\mathbf v=\\mathbf{0}\\,[/mathjaxinline] have a nonzero solution for vector [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline]? In other words, what are the eigenvalues of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline]?  **Answer:**   The values of [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline] that solve the **characteristic equation** [mathjaxinline]\\boxed {\\, \\displaystyle \\mathrm{det}\\left( \\lambda \\mathbf{I}- \\mathbf{A}\\right) =0.} \\,[/mathjaxinline]    This is a consequence of the following fundamental theorem in linear algebra.  ###  A fundamental theorem in linear algebra  **Theorem 7.2** Let [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{B}[/mathjaxinline] be a [mathjaxinline]n\\times n[/mathjaxinline] square matrix. Then the equation [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{B}\\mathbf{x}= \\mathbf{0}\\,[/mathjaxinline] has a nonzero solution if and only if [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{B}= 0.[/mathjaxinline]  For [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{B}= \\lambda \\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}, \\,[/mathjaxinline] this theorem can be restated as  **Theorem 7.3** Let [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] be a [mathjaxinline]n\\times n[/mathjaxinline] matrix. Then a scalar [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline] is an eigenvalue of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] if and only if [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\, \\mathrm{det}\\left(\\lambda \\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}\\right)=0[/mathjaxinline].  [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Definition 7.4** The function  [mathjax]\\, \\displaystyle P(\\lambda )=\\mathrm{det}\\left(\\lambda \\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A}\\right)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      is called the **characteristic polynomial** of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}.[/mathjaxinline] The roots of [mathjaxinline]\\, P(\\lambda )[/mathjaxinline] are the eigenvalues of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline].  For a [mathjaxinline]\\, 2 \\times 2\\,[/mathjaxinline] matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A},\\,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]P\\left(\\lambda \\right)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a quadratic polynomial in the variable [mathjaxinline]\\lambda .\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] You will find that the coefficient of the [mathjaxinline]\\lambda ^2[/mathjaxinline] is always [mathjaxinline]1.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] So solving for [mathjaxinline]\\lambda ,\\,[/mathjaxinline] or in other words, finding the eigenvalues of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A},\\,[/mathjaxinline] generally requires the quadratic formula.     **Warning:** We often calculate the eigenvalues by finding the roots of [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{det}(\\mathbf{A}-\\lambda \\mathbf{I})[/mathjaxinline] instead. This turns out to be the same as the roots of [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{det}(\\lambda \\mathbf{I}- \\mathbf{A})[/mathjaxinline]. The polynomials are in fact equal if [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] is even, and one is the negative of the other when [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] is odd. (The reason is that changing the signs of all [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] rows of the matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}-\\lambda \\mathbf{I}[/mathjaxinline] flips the sign of the determinant [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] times.) Usually we care only about the **roots** of the polynomial (the eigenvalues), so negating the whole polynomial doesn't make a difference. In any case, [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{det}(\\mathbf{A}-\\lambda \\mathbf{I}) = \\mathrm{det}(\\lambda \\mathbf{I}-\\mathbf{A})[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]2 \\times 2[/mathjaxinline] matrices (since [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline] is even).  **Example 7.5** What is the characteristic polynomial of the matrix  [mathjax]\\mathbf{A}= \\begin{pmatrix} -1& 3\\\\\\ 2& 1 \\end{pmatrix}?[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Solution:** The characteristic polynomial of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{det}( \\mathbf{A}-\\lambda \\mathbf{I})[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{det}\\left(\\begin{pmatrix} -1& 3\\\\\\ 2& 1 \\end{pmatrix} - \\lambda \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\\\\\ 0 & 1 \\end{pmatrix} \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{det}\\begin{pmatrix} -1 - \\lambda & 3\\\\\\ 2& 1 - \\lambda \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (-1-\\lambda )(1-\\lambda )-(3)(2)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda ^2-7.[/mathjaxinline] |  |  Characteristic Polynomial of a Matrix", "filename": "13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Characteristic Polynomial of a Matrix"}

Solve the system   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(x,y)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle h(x,y)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |      to find all the critical points in the [mathjaxinline](x,y)[/mathjaxinline]-phase plane. At each critical point [mathjaxinline]\\, (a,b),\\,[/mathjaxinline] compute the [mathjaxinline]2 \\times 2[/mathjaxinline] matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}=\\mathbf{J}(a,b)\\,[/mathjaxinline] by evaluating [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{J}(x,y)[/mathjaxinline] at [mathjaxinline](a,b).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] The linear approximation of the system near [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline] is then   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} \\dot{X} \\\\\\ \\dot{Y} \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}\\begin{pmatrix} X \\\\\\ Y \\end{pmatrix} \\qquad \\text{where }\\, \\begin{pmatrix} X\\\\\\ Y\\end{pmatrix}\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} x-a\\\\\\ y-b\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Mark the critical point [mathjaxinline]\\, (a,b)\\,[/mathjaxinline] in the [mathjaxinline]\\, (x,y)[/mathjaxinline]-plane, and draw a miniature copy of the phase portrait of the linear approximation centered at [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline]. Indicate with arrowheads the direction of motion on the trajectories near the critical point.  **Warning:** This step is justified only if the linearized system is **structurally stable** . That is, if the matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] lies in one of the big regions in the trace- determinant plane, or equivalently, if the phase portrait of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] is a saddle, a node, or a spiral. We will discuss this in more detail in the next lecture.    4. Connect trajectories emanating from or approaching critical points, while making sure **trajectories never cross or touch** . Trajectories can appear to meet at critical points (as [mathjaxinline]t \\rightarrow \\pm \\infty[/mathjaxinline]). If there are nearly parallel trajectories which seem to point in opposite directions, then this often means that you made a mistake in one of the previous steps, or you made a drawing error.   Steps to sketch full phase portrait", "filename": "31_pendulums-tab14-text1.html", "title": "Steps to sketch full phase portrait"}

{"pageid": 90, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@33_autonomoussystemsstability/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@33_autonomoussystemsstability-tab8", "text": "The big picture suggests that all trajectories in the first quadrant tend to [mathjaxinline]\\, (1,2)\\,[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]t \\to +\\infty[/mathjaxinline]. In other words, as long as there were some deer and some wolves to begin with, eventually the populations stabilize at about [mathjaxinline]1000[/mathjaxinline] deer and [mathjaxinline]200[/mathjaxinline] wolves (recall the units of deer are in [mathjaxinline]\\text{thousands}[/mathjaxinline] and the units of wolves in [mathjaxinline]\\text{hundreds}[/mathjaxinline]).    Recall the deer-wolf system:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 3x-x^2 -xy[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y-y^2+xy.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Our goal is to show that for this model, whenever [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(x(0),y(0)\\right)=(x_0,y_0)\\,[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]\\, x_0>0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]y_0>0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] then [mathjaxinline]\\left(x(t),y(t)\\right)\\to (1,2)\\,[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]\\, t\\to \\infty[/mathjaxinline].  Where can a trajectory that starts in the first quadrant go? A trajectory that starts in the first quadrant could escape in four ways: up, down, left, and right. We need to rule out all four.  **Step 1.** Because there are trajectories lying along both the positive [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]- and positive [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]-axes, and trajectories cannot touch, any trajectory that starts in the first quadrant cannot cross the positive axes. The only caveat is a trajectory might tend to one of the critical points.  ![There are stable trajectories lying along the vertical axis tending towards the critical point \\(0,1\\). There are stable trajectories along the horizontal axis tending towards the critical point \\(3,0\\).](/static/images/u7s2_fencesleft.svg)  **Step 2.** Any trajectory that start in the first quadrant cannot tend to any of the critical points on the [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]- or [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]- axes, because of the phase portrait types at these critical points:    * [mathjaxinline]\\, (0,0)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a nodal source,     * [mathjaxinline]\\, (3,0)\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline](0,1)[/mathjaxinline] are saddles whose incoming eigenlines lie along the axes.   Therefore, all trajectories that start in the first quadrant stay within the first quadrant.   **Remark:** Showing that all trajectories that start in the first quadrant are trapped in the first quadrant is part of validating our model, since [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] represent populations and do not make sense as negative numbers.  **Step 3.** Any trajectory that starts in the first quadrant cannot escape to infinity.  **No escape to the right:**  The first DE of the system gives the following inequality in the first quadrant whenever [mathjaxinline]\\, x>3\\,[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]\\dot{x} = 3x - x^2 - xy \\, <\\, 3x-x^2\\, <\\, 0 \\qquad (x>3,\\, y>0).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This means along each vertical line [mathjaxinline]\\, x=c,\\,[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]\\, c>3,\\,[/mathjaxinline] trajectories are moving leftwards. And since trajectories are moving leftwards on **all** vertical lines to the right of [mathjaxinline]x=3,\\,[/mathjaxinline] any trajectory that starts to the right of [mathjaxinline]\\, x=3\\,[/mathjaxinline] can settle down only in the vertical strip [mathjaxinline]\\, 0\\le x \\le 3.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline]    Each of the vertical lines [mathjaxinline]\\, x=c\\,[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]c>3\\,[/mathjaxinline] behaves like a fence preventing any trajectory on its left to cross to its right. In general, a **fence** is a curve or a line on the phase plane that block trajectories from crossing from one (or both) side(s).    ![Any vertical line drawn in the region x > 3 is a fence because one a trajectory crosses this line from right to left, it stays to the left of the line. All trajectories that begin in the first quadrant end up in the region y greater than 0 and 0 less than x less than 3.](/static/images/u7s2_fencesright.svg)  So far, we can conclude that all trajectories in the first quadrant will eventually enter the vertical strip [mathjaxinline]\\, 0\\le x \\le 3\\,[/mathjaxinline] and never leave.  **No escape to the top:**  In the region [mathjaxinline]\\, 0\\le x \\le 3,\\, y>4,\\,[/mathjaxinline] the second DE of the system gives the following inequality:  [mathjax]\\dot{y} \\, =\\, y - y^2 + xy \\, \\le \\, y -y^2 + 3 y \\, =\\, 4y - y^2\\, <\\, 0\\qquad ( 0\\le x \\le 3,\\, y>4).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Hence, along all horizontal segments [mathjaxinline]\\, y=d\\,[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]\\, d>4\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, 0 \\le x \\le 3[/mathjaxinline], trajectories move downwards and can only settle down in the rectangle [mathjaxinline]y\\leq 4,\\, 0 \\le x \\le 3[/mathjaxinline]. Any horizontal segment [mathjaxinline]y=d\\,[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]\\, d>4\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a fence.    ![Horizontal line segments between the y axis and the vertical line at x equal 3 are fences if the value of y is greater than 4. Trajectories move from top to down through these fences.](/static/images/u7s2_fencestop.svg)  (You might think you could fence in the trajectories from the top first and the right side second, but in fact, the order matters since we do need to first restrict to [mathjaxinline]\\, x\\le 3\\,[/mathjaxinline] to get the inequality [mathjaxinline]\\, y-y^2+xy\\leq 4y-y^2\\,[/mathjaxinline] above.)    To summarize, there are fences on all four sides. There are the obvious ones which are trajectories: the positive [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]-axes. There are also other curves, the vertical lines [mathjaxinline]x=c\\,[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]c>3,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and the horizontal segments [mathjaxinline]\\, y=d,\\,[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]\\, d>4\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, 0 \\le x \\le 3,\\,[/mathjaxinline] which are not trajectories but nonetheless block trajectories from crossing from one side.  **Conclusion:** All trajectories starting in the first quadrant, where [mathjaxinline]x>0,\\, y>0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] eventually enter the finite rectangle [mathjaxinline]0\\le x\\le 3,\\, 0\\le y \\le 4[/mathjaxinline] and stay there. This is small enough that a numerical simulation can now give supporting evidence that all trajectories starting in the first quadrant do tend to the stable critical point [mathjaxinline]\\, (1,2)[/mathjaxinline]. We will use the mathlet below for the numerical simulation. There is a rigorous proof based on fences and finding shrinking regions that trapped the trajectories.    The mathlet below display trajectories in the region [mathjaxinline]\\, 0\\le x\\le 3,\\, 0\\le y \\le 4.\\,[/mathjaxinline] Reproduce the figure above by selecting the second system in the dropdown menu:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (a+bx+cy)x[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.133)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (d+fx+hy)y[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.134)      and using the sliders to choose the appropriate values for the parameters [mathjaxinline]\\, (a=3,\\, b=-1,\\, c=-1,\\, d=1,\\, f=1,\\, h=-1).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline]   Click on the \u201cdrag axes\" button and drag to the first quadrant. and then use the slider below the phase portrait to zoom in to this region.  Fences", "filename": "33_autonomoussystemsstability-tab8-text1.html", "title": "Fences"}

Select the second system in the dropdown menu:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (a+bx+cy)x[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.148)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (d+fx+hy)y[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.149)      and use the sliders to choose the appropriate values for the parameters [mathjaxinline]\\, (a=-1,\\, b=0,\\, c=1,\\, d=1,\\, f=-1,\\, h=0).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] (Beware that the parameters have different names and signs in the mathlet than in the text above)   Click on the \u201cdrag axes\" button and drag to the first quadrant. and then use the slider below the phase portrait to zoom in to this region.  **Qualitative behavior using the mathlet:**   **Question 11.1** Slightly adjust the parameters in the shark-food fish system (named [mathjaxinline]a,\\, c,\\, d,\\, f\\,[/mathjaxinline] in the mathlet). How does the phase portrait change? Is it still a nonlinear center?  ###  Answer:      Yes. The phase portrait includes a nonlinear center with clockwise motion in the first quadrant as long as the signs of these parameters are not changed, so [mathjaxinline]\\, a,\\, b,\\, c,\\, d\\, >0[/mathjaxinline] (or in the mathlet [mathjaxinline]\\, a,\\, f <0,\\, c,\\, d>0[/mathjaxinline]).    This means that the population exhibits periodic behavior.As the shark population [mathjaxinline]\\, x\\,[/mathjaxinline] increases, the food fish get eaten up and so their population [mathjaxinline]\\, y\\,[/mathjaxinline] decreases. The decrease in food then leads to a decrease in the shark population [mathjaxinline],\\, x,\\,[/mathjaxinline] which in turn allows more food fish to grow and hence an increase in [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]. With more food, the shark population [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] increases again and the cycle repeats.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Question 11.2** How do slight adjustments of the parameters change the location of the critical point [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\left(\\frac{c}{d},\\, \\frac{a}{b}\\right)[/mathjaxinline]? What does that mean physically?    * (As in the video), what if the growth rates of both sharks and food fish are decreased due to indiscriminate fishing, so the growth rate of sharks changes from [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{-a}} \\,[/mathjaxinline] **to** [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{-(a+k)}} ,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and the growth rate of food fish is changed from [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{+c}} \\,[/mathjaxinline] **to** [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{+(c-k)}} \\,[/mathjaxinline]?   ###  Answer:  The critical point then moves to [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left(\\frac{c-k}{d},\\, \\frac{a+k }{b}\\right).\\,[/mathjaxinline] This translates to an increase in the food fish population, but a decrease in the shark population. In any predator- prey scenario modeled by this system, any indiscriminate killing of both predator and prey leads to a decrease in the predator population but an increase in the prey population!  ![The original system is a nonlinear center that looks circular about the critical point, but further away from the critical point, the circles are deformed into rounded triangle shapes. ](/static/images/u7s2_nonlinearcenter.svg)| ![With indiscriminate fishing, the circle becomes an ellipse that is taller than it is wide, and the triangles are squished towards the y axis and are taller and skinnier.](/static/images/u7s2_nonlinearcenterfishing.svg)   ---|---   original shark-food fish system|  shark-food fish system with indiscriminate fishing      [Show](javascript: {return false;})    * What happens if [mathjaxinline]\\, x\\,[/mathjaxinline] represents the population of a different species of sharks that need less food to grow, so that [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{b}} \\,[/mathjaxinline] **is increased to** [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{b+k}}[/mathjaxinline]?   ###  Answer:     The critical point moves downwards to [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left(\\frac{c}{d},\\, \\frac{a}{b+k}\\right).\\,[/mathjaxinline] The population of sharks grows faster with the same number of food fish, so the top of the cycles in the nonlinear center is 'flatter.\" Also, since the sharks need less food to grow, its population will only stop increasing when the number of food fish is lower. The relative fluctuation of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] is larger since the sharks respond more strongly to their food supply. ![The original system is a nonlinear center that looks circular about the critical point, but further away from the critical point, the circles are deformed into rounded triangle shapes. ](/static/images/u7s2_nonlinearcenter.svg)| ![With less hungry sharks, the circle becomes an ellipse that is shorter and wider, and the triangles are squished towards the x axis and are shorter and wider.](/static/images/u7s2_nonlinearcenterbiggerb.svg)   ---|---   original shark-food fish system|  shark with less appetite and food fish system      [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Exploration and qualitative behavior", "filename": "33_autonomoussystemsstability-tab11-text1.html", "title": "Exploration and qualitative behavior"}

Generally,    * If all trajectories tend to [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{0}[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]t \\to +\\infty[/mathjaxinline], the system is called **stable.**    * If some trajectories are unbounded as [mathjaxinline]t \\to +\\infty[/mathjaxinline], then the system is called **unstable.**    * In the borderline case in which all solutions are bounded, but do not all tend to [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{0},\\,[/mathjaxinline] the system is called **semistable** (or **neutrally stable** ). {"pageid": 101, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab6", "text": "To compute eigenvalues, we will need **determinants**. Let us review it now.     **Determinant of a [mathjaxinline]2 \\times 2[/mathjaxinline] matrix**  Let [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] be a [mathjaxinline]2 \\times 2\\,[/mathjaxinline] matrix  [mathjax]\\mathbf{A}=\\begin{pmatrix} a& b\\\\\\ c& d \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      then the **determinant** of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A},\\,[/mathjaxinline] denoted [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{det}(\\mathbf{A}),\\,[/mathjaxinline] is the **scalar**  [mathjax]\\mathrm{det}(\\mathbf{A}) = \\mathrm{det}\\begin{pmatrix} a& b\\\\\\ c& d \\end{pmatrix} =\\, ad-bc.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      There are several alternative notations for the determinant:  [mathjax]\\mathrm{det}(\\mathbf{A}) = \\left|\\mathbf{A}\\right| =\\mathrm{det}\\begin{pmatrix} a& b\\\\\\ c& d \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{vmatrix} a& b\\\\\\ c& d \\end{vmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Example 6.1**  [mathjax]\\mathrm{det}\\begin{pmatrix} -1& 3\\\\\\ 2& 1 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{vmatrix} -1& 3\\\\\\ 2& 1 \\end{vmatrix} \\, =\\, (-1)(1)-(3)(2)\\, =\\, -7.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Determinants", "filename": "13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab6-text1.html", "title": "Determinants"}

{"pageid": 102, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@15_stability/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@15_stability-tab13", "text": "Stability is a question of what happens to the solutions of a fixed system of ODEs. There is a different, equally important question of what happens if the system of ODEs itself is changed slightly, by perturbing the matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] This is addressed by the **structural stability** of the system.  **Definition 13.1** If the phase portrait type is robust in the sense that small perturbations in the entries of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] do not change the type of the phase portrait, then the system is called **structurally stable** .  Structurally stable systems are those corresponding to the large regions in the trace-determinant plane, not the borderline cases. Hence, for a [mathjaxinline]2 \\times 2[/mathjaxinline] matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline], the system [mathjaxinline]\\dot{\\mathbf{x}}=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline] is structurally stable if and only if the eigenvalues of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] are    * real, distinct and nonzero, corresponding to saddles, node sources or node sinks;     * complex with nonzero real part, corresponding to spirals.   ![The boundaries on the Trace Determinant plane are where systems are structurally unstable: along the positive Det axis, along the critical parabola, and along the horizontal Tr axis.](/static/images/u3s4_tdfullred.svg)    **Figure 21** : The systems on the **boundaries** between different phase portrait types are **structurally unstable.**  Let us look at an example of a structurally unstable system.  **Two connected fluid tanks:**    Recall the system describing two connected nonleaking fluid storage tanks:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}\\, =\\, \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}\\qquad \\text{where}\\, \\, \\mathbf{A}=\\begin{pmatrix} -1 & 1\\\\\\ 1 & -1\\end{pmatrix},\\qquad \\mathbf{x}=\\begin{pmatrix} h_1\\\\\\ h_2\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.92)   ---|---|---|---      where [mathjaxinline]\\, h_1,\\, h_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] are the heights of fluid in the two tanks.    We have previously found that this system has eigenvalues [mathjaxinline]\\, 0\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, -2.\\,[/mathjaxinline] Therefore, it is situated on the negative [mathjaxinline]\\, \\text{Tr}\\,[/mathjaxinline]-axis on the trace-determinant plane. Its phase portrait is a comb. This is a **semistable** system since every trajectory on the phase plane approaches a point on the [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline]-eigenline.  However, this is a **structurally unstable** system. To see this, let us perturb the lower right entry of the matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline]  **System with one leaky tank:**    ![Two large cylindrical tanks are connected at the bottom by a very thin pipe. The height of fluid in tank 1 is h1, the height of fluid in tank 2 is h2. There is a leak in tank 2. ](/static/images/tanks2leaking_copy.svg)     **Figure 22** : Fluid is leaking from tank 2 at a rate of [mathjaxinline]\\, bh_2[/mathjaxinline]      Recall that the system describing the heights of fluid in two connected tanks with tank 2 leaking at a rate [mathjaxinline]b h_2[/mathjaxinline] is  | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}\\, =\\, \\widetilde{\\mathbf{A}}\\mathbf{x}\\qquad \\text{where}\\, \\, \\widetilde{\\mathbf{A}}=\\begin{pmatrix} -1 & 1\\\\\\ 1 & -1-b\\end{pmatrix},\\qquad \\mathbf{x}=\\begin{pmatrix} h_1\\\\\\ h_2\\end{pmatrix} \\, \\text{and }\\, b>0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.93)   ---|---|---|---      Note that the matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\widetilde{\\mathbf{A}}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a perturbation of the matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}=\\begin{pmatrix} -1 & 1\\\\\\ 1 & -1\\end{pmatrix}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] The eigenvalues of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\widetilde{\\mathbf{A}}\\,[/mathjaxinline] are the roots of the characteristic polynomial:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda ^2-\\mathrm{tr}\\widetilde{\\mathbf{A}}\\lambda +\\mathrm{det}\\widetilde{\\mathbf{A}}\\, =\\, \\lambda ^2-(-2-b)\\lambda +b[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda \\, =\\, \\frac{-(2+b)\\pm \\sqrt{(2+b)^2-4b}}{2}\\, \\qquad (\\text{where }\\, b>0).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.94)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---      The eigenvalues of [mathjaxinline]\\widetilde{\\mathbf{A}}[/mathjaxinline] are real, distinct and **both negative** , as long as [mathjaxinline]\\, b>0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] giving a node sink as the phase portrait. The perturbed system is **stable** , since all phase plane trajectories tend to the origin. Physically, this means both tanks eventually empty out as long as there is a leak.    (If [mathjaxinline]\\, b<0\\,[/mathjaxinline] instead, which corresponds to fluid continuously flowing into tank 2, then the perturbed system is unstable. The amount of fluid in the two tanks will become infinite; or more realistically, both tanks will eventually overflow!)     **Conclusion:**   We see that the phase portrait of the system with [mathjaxinline]\\, b=0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] a comb, is of a different type than the phase portrait of a system with any value of [mathjaxinline]\\, b\\,[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]\\, b>0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] a nodal sink. The qualitative behavior of the system with [mathjaxinline]b=0[/mathjaxinline] is changed drastically by the slightest change in [mathjaxinline]\\, b.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Therefore, the system with [mathjaxinline]\\, b=0\\,[/mathjaxinline] is structurally unstable.  Structural stability", "filename": "15_stability-tab13-text1.html", "title": "Structural stability"}

{"pageid": 103, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab5", "text": "Recall that to find nonzero solutions [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf ve^{\\lambda t}\\,[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x},\\,[/mathjaxinline] we need to solve [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\left(\\mathbf{A}-\\lambda \\mathbf{I}\\right) \\mathbf v= \\mathbf{0}[/mathjaxinline] for nonzero vectors [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Finding all possible values of [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline] and, for each [mathjaxinline]\\lambda ,\\,[/mathjaxinline] all vectors [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v\\,[/mathjaxinline] satisfying [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\left(\\mathbf{A}-\\lambda \\mathbf{I}\\right)\\mathbf v=\\mathbf{0}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is known as the **eigenvalue-eigenvector problem** .     **Definition 5.1** Let [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] be a [mathjaxinline]2 \\times 2[/mathjaxinline] matrix.    * An **eigenvalue** [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline] of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] is a scalar such that [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf v= \\lambda \\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] for some **nonzero** vector [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline].     * An **eigenvector** [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] associated with an eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]\\lambda \\,[/mathjaxinline] is a **nonzero** vector [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf v= \\lambda \\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline].   We also say an eigenvector \u201ccorresponding to,\" or \u201cbelonging to\" an eigenvalue.  **Warning:** The zero vector [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v=\\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] is never an eigenvector. However, [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda =0\\,[/mathjaxinline] can be an eigenvalue.  The terminology is the same for general [mathjaxinline]N \\times N[/mathjaxinline] systems but we will only consider the case [mathjaxinline]N>2[/mathjaxinline] in a later course, _Linear algebra and systems of differential equations_.  **Example 5.2** Let [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}= \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & -2 \\\\\\ -1 & 0 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] and let [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v= \\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\\\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Is [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] an eigenvector of [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline]?  **Solution:** The calculation  [mathjax]\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf v= \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & -2 \\\\\\ -1 & 0 \\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\\\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\\\\\ -2 \\end{pmatrix} = 2 \\mathbf v,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      shows that [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] is an eigenvector, and that the associated eigenvalue is [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline].  Eigenvalue and eigenvectors", "filename": "13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Eigenvalue and eigenvectors"}

{"pageid": 106, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@recitation18/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@recitation18-tab3", "text": "Look at the phase portrait of the system for [mathjaxinline]\\, a=0\\,[/mathjaxinline], that is, for the case that the shark population remains constant in the absence of squids:  Use the mathlet below to display the phase portrait of this system by first selecting the second system in the dropdown menu:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (a+bx+cy)x[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.200)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (d+fx+hy)y[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.201)      Use the sliders to set the parameters in the mathlet to the appropriate values: [mathjaxinline]\\, a=0,\\, b=0,\\, c=1,\\, d=1,\\, f=-1,\\, h=0.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] (Beware that the parameters are named by different letters in the mathlet than in the text above.) {"pageid": 107, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab11", "text": "The last step to solving a [mathjaxinline]2 \\times 2[/mathjaxinline] system, [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x},\\,[/mathjaxinline] is to assemble the general solution from the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of the coefficient matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}.[/mathjaxinline]  **General solution to** [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{\\dot{\\mathbf{x}}=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}}} \\,[/mathjaxinline] **where** [mathjaxinline]\\, {\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{A}}} \\,[/mathjaxinline] **has 2 distinct eigenvalues** :  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\mathbf{x}(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_1 \\mathbf v_1 e^{\\lambda _1 t}+c_2 \\mathbf v_2 e^{\\lambda _2 t}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.90)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      where [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_1\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_2[/mathjaxinline] are eigenvectors of the eigenvalues [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _2[/mathjaxinline] respectively, and [mathjaxinline]\\, c_1,c_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] are arbitrary scalars. In other words, the general solution is the superposition of two basic solutions of the form [mathjaxinline]e^{\\lambda t} \\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline].  **Initial conditions**  The two unknown constants [mathjaxinline]c_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]c_2[/mathjaxinline] in the general solution are to be determined by the initial conditions. Since there are two constants, we need two initial conditions, given in vector notation as  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\mathbf{x}(a)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{b}\\qquad \\text{where } \\, \\mathbf{b}=\\begin{pmatrix} b_1\\\\\\ b_2\\end{pmatrix} \\, \\text{is a constant vector}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.91)   ---|---|---|---|---|---       **Example 11.1** Consider again the matrix in our previous example  [mathjax]\\mathbf{A}=\\begin{pmatrix} 1 & -2 \\\\\\ -1 & 0 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Find the general solution to the system [mathjaxinline]\\dot{\\mathbf{x}}=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline] and the solution satisfying the initial condition [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{x}(0)=\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline].  **Solution:**    Recall we have already found for the matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline]:    * [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda _1=2, \\, \\, \\mathbf v_1=\\begin{pmatrix} -2 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix},\\,[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda _2=-1,\\, \\, \\mathbf v_2 = \\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}.\\,[/mathjaxinline]   The general solution to the system is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{x}(t)= \\begin{pmatrix} x(t) \\\\\\ y(t) \\end{pmatrix} = c_1\\begin{pmatrix} -2 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix} e^{2t} + c_2 \\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}e^{-t},[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.92)   ---|---|---|---      where [mathjaxinline]\\, c_1 \\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, c_2 \\,[/mathjaxinline] are arbitrary scalars.    To find the solution that satisfies the initial condition [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{x}(0)=\\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix},\\,[/mathjaxinline] we need to solve the following vector equation for [mathjaxinline]c_1,\\, c_2[/mathjaxinline]:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\mathbf{x}(0)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_1\\begin{pmatrix} -2 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix} + c_2 \\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix},[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.93)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      This is equivalent to the system of two linear equations:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle -2c_1+c_2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 1[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.94)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_1+c_2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.95)      Substituting [mathjaxinline]c_2=-c_1[/mathjaxinline] into the first equation, we get [mathjaxinline]c_1=-\\frac{1}{3},\\, c_2=\\frac{1}{3}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline]    Note that the initial condition can also be written in matrix notation:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} -2& 1\\\\\\ 1& 1\\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} c_1\\\\\\ c_2\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.96)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Writing the initial condition in matrix notation will be very helpful when solving initial value problems for [mathjaxinline]N\\times N[/mathjaxinline] systems, which we will discuss in the course _Linear algebra and systems of differential equations_.  General solution to systems of DE", "filename": "13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab11-text1.html", "title": "General solution to systems of DE"}

This particular nonlinear DE can be solved exactly. Nonetheless, linearization allows us to approximate solutions near critical points without solving the full nonlinear DE. It can also be applied to other autonomous ODEs for which one cannot find an exact formula.  Suppose we are interested in solutions to the logistic equation in the region [mathjaxinline]\\, 0<y<3.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] In the range [mathjaxinline]0.1<y<2.9,\\,[/mathjaxinline] away from the critical points, numerical simulation can give us a clear picture of the solutions. On the other hand, near the critical points [mathjaxinline]\\, y=0\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, y=3,\\,[/mathjaxinline] numerical methods may not give a clear or accurate picture, especially of the asymptotic behavior as [mathjaxinline]\\, t \\to -\\infty[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, t \\to +\\infty .\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Instead, we use linear approximation near each critical point.    * Consider [mathjaxinline]y \\approx 0[/mathjaxinline], which is of interest when [mathjaxinline]t \\to -\\infty ,\\,[/mathjaxinline] that is, when studying the origins of the population. The linear approximation of [mathjaxinline]\\, f(y)\\,[/mathjaxinline] near [mathjaxinline]\\, y=0\\,[/mathjaxinline] gives   [mathjax]\\dot{y} = f(y) = 3y-y^2 \\approx 3y.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Solving the linearized DE, we have  [mathjax]y \\approx a e^{3t}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      for some constant [mathjaxinline]a\\,[/mathjaxinline] as [mathjaxinline]\\, t\\to -\\infty .\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline]Physically, this means that when the population begins to grow from a very small number, solutions to the logistic equation obey approximately exponential growth. Later, the competition for food or space, represented by the [mathjaxinline]-y^2[/mathjaxinline] term in the DE, becomes too large to ignore.    * Consider [mathjaxinline]y \\approx 3[/mathjaxinline], which is of interest when [mathjaxinline]\\, t \\to +\\infty , \\,[/mathjaxinline] that is, when studying the fate of the population. Because [mathjaxinline]\\, y=3\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a critical point, [mathjaxinline]\\, f(3)=0.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Therefore, The best linear approximation to [mathjaxinline]\\, f(y)\\,[/mathjaxinline] when [mathjaxinline]\\, y \\approx 3\\,[/mathjaxinline] is   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle f(y)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(y) \\approx -3(y-3),[/mathjax]|   ---|---      which can be thought of as a DE for [mathjaxinline]y-3[/mathjaxinline]:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot{(y-3)}\\approx constant}),[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.27)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      and then use the solution [mathjaxinline]Y[/mathjaxinline] to approximate [mathjaxinline]y-3. \\,[/mathjaxinline] y\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a solution to the original nonlinear DE. Therefore,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle y-3\\, \\approx \\, Y[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longleftrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y \\, \\approx \\, 3+Y\\, =\\, 3+be^{-3t}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.29)   ---|---|---|---|---|---       **Reminder:** This approximation works only near [mathjaxinline]\\, y=3.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] This is well adapted to [mathjaxinline]\\, t\\to \\infty \\,[/mathjaxinline] because [mathjaxinline]\\, Y\\underset {t\\to \\infty }{\\to } 0[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 109, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@33_autonomoussystemsstability/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@33_autonomoussystemsstability-tab9", "text": "The autonomous system that describes the predator-prey system of sharks and food fish is:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(-a+by)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.135)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y(c-dx)\\qquad \\text{where }\\, \\, a,\\, b,\\, c,\\, d\\, >0,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.136)      and [mathjaxinline]\\, x\\,[/mathjaxinline] is the population of sharks and [mathjaxinline]\\, y\\,[/mathjaxinline] is the population of food fish (called \"yumfish\" in the video), [mathjaxinline]\\, ,-a,\\, c\\,[/mathjaxinline] are the natural growth rates of the sharks and food fish respectively, and [mathjaxinline]\\, b\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, d\\,[/mathjaxinline] determine how interactions between the two species affect the rate of change of the shark and food fish populations respectively.    This model is simpler than the deer-wolf system in that the logistic terms proportional to [mathjaxinline]\\, x^2\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, y^2\\,[/mathjaxinline] are zero in both DEs.    There are two critical points: [mathjaxinline]\\, (0,0)\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\left(\\frac{c}{d},\\, \\frac{a}{b}\\right).\\,[/mathjaxinline] The Jacobian matrix is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{J}(x,y)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} -a+by& bx\\\\\\ -dy& c-dx\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.137)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      The linearized system at [mathjaxinline]\\, (0,0)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is determined by [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\mathbf{J}(0,0)=\\, \\begin{pmatrix} -a& 0\\\\\\ 0& c\\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline] (where [mathjaxinline]\\, a,c>0\\,[/mathjaxinline] ) and is a saddle. Since saddles are **structurally stable** , the phase portrait of the nonlinear system contains a saddle at the critical point [mathjaxinline]\\, (0,0).[/mathjaxinline]    We will now linearize the system at the other critical point [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\left(\\frac{c}{d},\\, \\frac{a}{b}\\right).\\,[/mathjaxinline]    Structurally unstable example", "filename": "33_autonomoussystemsstability-tab9-text1.html", "title": "Structurally unstable example"}

{"pageid": 110, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@forum/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@forum-tab1", "text": "The discussion forum is the tool for connecting with the community of online learners in this course. Use the forum to ask questions, seek clarifications, report bugs, and start or respond to topical discussions.  On most pages, there is a link at the bottom, which says \u201cshow discussion\". Clicking this link will show the discussion forum associated with the videos and problems on that page. (Go ahead and click show discussion at the bottom of this page, find the post titled \"Hello and Welcome!\" and introduce yourself!)  ### \u201cNetiquette\": What to do    *  **Be polite. Make sure that your posts are respectful of the other students and staff in the course.**    * Use the search button. Search for similar forum posts **before you post** using the magnifying glass icon. Many of your classmates will have the same question that you do! If you perform a search first, you may find the question and answer without needing to post yourself. This helps us keep the forum organized and useful!     * Reply to existing discussions when you see someone with the same question. This helps to organize responses.     * Use a descriptive and specific title to your post. This will attract the attention of TAs and classmates who can answer your question.     * Be very specific about where you need help. Are you stuck on a particular part of a problem? Are you confused by a particular concept? What have you done so far?     * Actively up-vote other posts, and other students will up-vote yours! The more up-votes your post has, the more likely they are to be seen.   ### \u201cNetiquette\": What not to do  Follow common writing practices for online communication:    * Avoid TYPING IN ALL CAPS. Some people read this as shouting, even if that is not your intention.     * Avoid **typing in bold**. Some people read this as shouting, even if that is not your intention.     * Avoid unnecessary symbols, abbreviated words, texting shorthand, and replacing words with numbers (e.g. Pls don't rplce wrds w/#s).     * Avoid repeating letters or reeeeepeeaattinggggg chaaracterrrss.     * Avoid excessive punctuation!!!!!!!!   ### Cheating  We encourage you to communicate in the forum about problems, and get hints and help understanding the material from your fellow classmates and the course TAs. However:    * Please do not post solutions to lecture problems, homework problems (part A or part B), or final exam problems. These will be removed, and the student who posted will be contacted and dealt with individually.     * Do not post or copy solutions posted to the forum for any exercises. This is cheating. ( **Exception:** It is OK to post and copy solutions to recitation problems.)     * Do not copy solutions from yourself. This is cheating. (If you don't know what this means, you are not cheating.)   Discussion Forum", "filename": "forum-tab1-text1.html", "title": "Discussion Forum"}

{"pageid": 112, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@33_autonomoussystemsstability/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@33_autonomoussystemsstability-tab10", "text": "If the linearization at a critical point of an autonomous system is structurally unstable, i.e. a center, a comb, or another degenerate portrait, then the original autonomous system may not behave in the same way as the linearized system near the critical point.  For example, if a critical point is a **center** , then the original nonlinear system may behave like **any** of the possibilities below:    * a **nonlinear center** , in which the trajectories are periodic, but not necessarily exact ellipses,     * a spiral source,     * a spiral sink.   **Example 10.1** Recall the sharks and food fish system:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(-a+by)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.138)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y(c-dx)\\qquad \\text{where }\\, \\, a,\\, b,\\, c,\\, d\\, >0,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.139)      What is the behavior of this system near the critical point [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\left(\\frac{c}{d},\\, \\frac{a}{b}\\right)\\,[/mathjaxinline]?  **Solution:** The linearized system at the critical point [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\left(\\frac{c}{d},\\, \\frac{a}{b}\\right)\\,[/mathjaxinline] is a center, since the Jacobian matrix evaluated at the critical point is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\mathbf{J}\\left(\\frac{c}{d},\\, \\frac{a}{b}\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left.\\begin{pmatrix} -a+by& bx\\\\\\ -dy& c-dx\\end{pmatrix}\\right|_{\\left(\\frac{c}{d},\\, \\frac{a}{b}\\right)}\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} \\displaystyle 0& \\displaystyle \\frac{bc}{d} \\\\\\ \\displaystyle -\\frac{ad}{b}& 0 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.140)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      The characteristic polynomial is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\lambda ^2+ac[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.141)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Since [mathjaxinline]\\, ac>0,\\,[/mathjaxinline] the eigenvalues are purely imaginary and equal [mathjaxinline]\\, \\pm i\\sqrt{ac}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] The phase portrait of the linearized system is therefore a center, which is **structurally unstable** . Alternately, we can see that the linearized system is structurally unstable by locating it on positive vertical axis on the trace-determinant plane, since [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathrm{tr}\\left(\\mathbf{J}\\left(\\frac{c}{d},\\, \\frac{a}{b}\\right)\\right)\\, =0\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathrm{det}\\left(\\mathbf{J}\\left(\\frac{c}{d},\\, \\frac{a}{b}\\right) \\right)>0.\\,[/mathjaxinline]    Therefore, the behavior of the original nonlinear system near this critical point can be a **spiral source** , a **spiral sink** , or a **nonlinear center**.    Here is a sketch of the phase portrait of the nonlinear autonomous system. For this purpose, we have fixed the system parameters [mathjaxinline]\\, a=b=c=d=1,\\,[/mathjaxinline] so the system is as in the video:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(-1+y)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.142)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y(1-x),[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.143)      and critical point of interest is [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(\\frac{c}{d},\\, \\frac{a}{b}\\right)=(1,1).[/mathjaxinline]    ![A nonlinear center that looks circular about the critical point, but further away from the critical point, the circles are deformed into rounded triangle shapes.](/static/images/u7s2_nonlinearcenter.svg)  You can use the mathlet below to reproduce the phase portrait. Select the second system in the dropdown menu:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (a+bx+cy)x[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.144)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (d+fx+hy)y[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.145)      and use the sliders to choose the appropriate values for the parameters [mathjaxinline]\\, (a=-1,\\, b=0,\\, c=1,\\, d=1,\\, f=-1,\\, h=0).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] (Beware that the parameters are named by different letters in the mathlet than in the text above.)   Click on the \u201cdrag axes\" button and drag to the first quadrant. and then use the slider below the phase portrait to zoom in to this region.  **Remark:** The mathlet provides numerical evidence that the shark-food fish system behaves as a nonlinear center at the critical point [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\mathbf{J}\\left(\\frac{c}{d},\\, \\frac{a}{b}\\right)=(1,1).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] But how much can we trust numerical simulations? One question to which numerical simulations have not been able to give a definite answer is, \u201cWhat is the fate of the solar system?\" For such extremely long term behavior, we have no hope of getting a precise answer from numerical simulations. Other trajectories are tangent to the eigenline corresponding to the eigenvalue with smaller absolute value at [mathjaxinline](0,0).[/mathjaxinline]     3. If the eigenvalues are **complex** , say [mathjaxinline]s\\pm i\\omega[/mathjaxinline], check the sign of [mathjaxinline]\\, s\\,[/mathjaxinline]:       * If [mathjaxinline]+[/mathjaxinline], **spiral source** , also known as **repelling spiral** .       * If [mathjaxinline]-[/mathjaxinline], **spiral sink** , also known as **attracting spiral** .       * If [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline], **center** .   You can explore these cases using the mathlet below.
