{"pageid": 122, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab13", "text": "**Steps to find the general solution to** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\dot{\\mathbf{x}}=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}}}[/mathjaxinline] **, where** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{A}}} \\,[/mathjaxinline] **is a** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{2 \\times 2}}[/mathjaxinline] **matrix with distinct eigenvalues:**        **Step 1.** Find the eigenvalues [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _1,\\, \\lambda _2\\,[/mathjaxinline] by solving [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathrm{det}( \\mathbf{A}-\\lambda \\mathbf{I})=0.\\,[/mathjaxinline]     **Formulas for the characteristic polynomial :**   In general, the characteristic polynomial of a matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}= \\begin{pmatrix} a& b\\\\\\ c& d \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] is  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{det}( \\mathbf{A}-\\lambda \\mathbf{I})[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda ^2 - (a+d) \\lambda + (ad - bc)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda ^2 - (\\mathrm{tr}\\mathbf{A})\\, \\lambda + \\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      **Step 2.** Find an eigenvector [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{\\mathbf v} \\,[/mathjaxinline] for each eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{\\lambda }\\,[/mathjaxinline] by solving the linear system [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left(\\mathbf{A}-\\lambda \\mathbf{I}\\right)\\mathbf v=\\mathbf{0}.[/mathjaxinline]     **Step 3.** Form the general solution from the eigenvalue-eigenvector pairs.    For each eigenvalue and eigenvector pair [mathjaxinline]\\, \\left(\\lambda ,\\mathbf v\\right),\\,[/mathjaxinline] the vector-valued function [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf ve^{\\lambda t} \\,[/mathjaxinline] is a solution to the system of ODEs we started with.  The general solution for the case when [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] has two distinct eigenvalues is  [mathjax]\\mathbf{x}(t)= c_1 \\mathbf v_1 e^{\\lambda _1 t}+c_2 \\mathbf v_2 e^{\\lambda _2 t}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_1\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_2[/mathjaxinline] are eigenvectors of [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _2[/mathjaxinline] respectively, and [mathjaxinline]\\, c_1,c_2\\,[/mathjaxinline] are arbitrary scalars.    The solutions [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v_1 e^{\\lambda _1 t}\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf v_2 e^{\\lambda _2 t}\\,[/mathjaxinline] that form a basis to the family of all solutions are sometimes called **normal modes** .  **Warning:**  We have been considering only [mathjaxinline]\\, 2\\times 2\\,[/mathjaxinline] matrices [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}\\,[/mathjaxinline] with 2 real distinct eigenvalues so far. The eigenvalues and eigenvectors may indeed be complex, and we will discuss finding a basis of real solutions in the next lecture. The case with repeated eigenvalues is far less common; we will discuss this case later.     **Example 13.2** Find the general solution [mathjaxinline](x(t),y(t))[/mathjaxinline] to the system  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = 3 x - y,[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -3 x + 5 y.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      In matrix form, this is [mathjaxinline]\\dot{\\mathbf{x}} = \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline], where [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}= \\begin{pmatrix} 3 & -1 \\\\\\ -3 & 5 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline].  **Step 1.** Find the eigenvalues.   The characteristic polynomial is:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{det}(\\mathbf{A}-\\lambda \\mathbf{I})[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda ^2 - 8 \\lambda + 12[/mathjaxinline] | | (2.98)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      where  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 8[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{tr}\\mathbf{A}=3+5[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.99)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 12[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}=3(5)-(-1)(-3)=12.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.100)      Alternatively, we can find the characteristic polynomial by directly computing [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\mathrm{det}\\left( \\mathbf{A}-\\lambda \\mathbf{I}\\right)[/mathjaxinline]:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{vmatrix} 3 -\\lambda & -1 \\\\\\ -3 & 5 -\\lambda \\\\\\ \\end{vmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (3-\\lambda )(5 -\\lambda ) - 3[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.101)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda ^2 - 8 \\lambda + 12.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.102)      This polynomial can be factored into  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\lambda ^2 - 8 \\lambda + 12[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\lambda -2)(\\lambda -6).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.103)   ---|---|---|---|---|---       **Step 2.** Find an eigenvector corresponding to each eigenvalue.  **For** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\lambda _1=2}}[/mathjaxinline] **:** We need to solve  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\mathbf{A}-2\\mathbf{I}) \\mathbf v= \\mathbf{0}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longleftrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & -1\\\\\\ -3 & 3 \\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} a_1 \\\\\\ a_2 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.104)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      By inspection, the nontrivial solutions to this system and hence the eigenvectors for the eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]\\, 2\\,[/mathjaxinline] are all nonzero scalar multiples of  [mathjax]\\mathbf v_1\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **For** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\lambda _2=6}}[/mathjaxinline] **:** We need to solve  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\mathbf{A}-6\\mathbf{I}) \\mathbf v= 0[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longleftrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} -3 & -1\\\\\\ -3 & -1 \\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} b_1 \\\\\\ b_2 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\\\\\ 0 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.105)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      We have the eigenvectors corresponding to the eigenvalue [mathjaxinline]\\, 6\\,[/mathjaxinline] are all nonzero scalar multiples of  [mathjax]\\mathbf v_2=\\begin{pmatrix} -1 \\\\\\ 3 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Step 3.** Build the general solution from the eigenvalue-eigenvector pairs.  We have two independent solutions,  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}e^{2t} , \\quad \\begin{pmatrix} -1 \\\\\\ 3 \\end{pmatrix}e^{6t}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The general solution is:  [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{x}(t)= c_1 \\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}e^{2t} + c_2 \\begin{pmatrix} -1 \\\\\\ 3 \\end{pmatrix}e^{6t}}} .[/mathjaxinline]  Solving 2 by 2 homogeneous systems", "filename": "13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab13-text2.html", "title": "Solving 2 by 2 homogeneous systems"}

{"pageid": 123, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@12_motivationforsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@12_motivationforsystems-tab6", "text": "Here's our first example.  You've been put in charge of part of a medicine manufacturing plant with two identical cylindrical storage tanks. One of these tanks, however, is defective, and liquid medicine leaks continuously out of a crack at the bottom. The tanks are filled with the medicine to different heights. They are connected to each other via a pipe at their bottoms, with valves that are initially closed. Our goal is to determine how the fluid will flow once we open the valves. To begin, we name the heights [mathjaxinline]h_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]h_2[/mathjaxinline] of the fluid in the two tanks.  ![Two large cylindrical tanks are connected at the bottom by a very thin pipe. The height of fluid in tank 1 is h1, the height of fluid in tank 2 is h2. There is a leak in tank 2. ](/static/images/tanks2leaking_copy.svg)     **Simplifying assumptions**  We are going to make the simplifying assumptions that we can model the flow linearly, and that the flow rate is proportional to the difference in fluid height. These assumptions are valid when the pipes have a small diameter relative to the overall size of the tanks, the geometry of the pipes and tanks is simple, and the fluid properties of the medicine work out.  In general, fluid flow is modeled by the Navier-Stokes equations, which form a system of partial differential equations, one of which is nonlinear. The study of fluids is beyond the scope of this course. However, doing a first approximation assuming linear behavior is a common first step in a modeling process, and well within our scope.  **Linearized problem with non-leaking tanks**  Let's start by solving a simpler problem, in which tank 2 is not leaking.  ![See caption](/static/images/tanks2color_copy.svg)    **Figure 11** : Two tanks with no leaks connected by a small pipe      Let [mathjaxinline]V_1[/mathjaxinline] be the volume of fluid in tank 1. The flow rate of fluid into tank [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] (from tank [mathjaxinline]2[/mathjaxinline]) is by definition [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\frac{dV_1}{dt}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline]   Since the tank is cylindrical, the rate of change in volume is given by the cross sectional area [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline] times the rate of change in height [mathjaxinline]h_1[/mathjaxinline] of fluid in tank 1 :  [mathjax]\\frac{dV_1}{dt} = A \\frac{dh_1}{dt}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      As mentioned above, we assume that the flow rate is proportional to the difference in heights:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{dV_1}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c(h_2-h_1)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.1)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      where [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] is the constant of proportionality (that has dimension [mathjaxinline][\\text{length}]^2 [\\text{time}]^{-1}[/mathjaxinline]). Therefore,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{dh_1}{dt} = \\frac{1}{A}\\frac{dV_1}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{c}{A}(h_2-h_1).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.2)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Note that the constant [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] is positive because when [mathjaxinline]h_2>h_1,\\,[/mathjaxinline] fluid flows into tank 1 so that [mathjaxinline]h_1[/mathjaxinline] is increasing. We usually set up differential equations so that parameters such as [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] are positive. This way we will be less prone to sign errors.    Similarly, for [mathjaxinline]h_2,\\,[/mathjaxinline] we have the differential equation  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{dh_2}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{c}{A}(h_1-h_2).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.3)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      This is consistent because if [mathjaxinline]h_1<h_2[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\frac{dh_2}{dt}=\\frac{c}{A}(h_1-h_2)<0[/mathjaxinline]. In other words, fluid flows out of tank 2. Notice the constant [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] is the same as before since the fluid leaving tank 2 goes into tank 1.    We can combine the two constants into a new constant [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle a= \\frac{c}{A}[/mathjaxinline] (that has dimension [mathjaxinline][\\text{time}]^{-1}[/mathjaxinline]) and rewrite the differential equations as  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dh_1}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle a(h_2-h_1)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dh_2}{dt}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle a(h_1-h_2).[/mathjaxinline] |  |      We now have two first order ODEs, each depending on **both** functions [mathjaxinline]h_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]h_2[/mathjaxinline]. We call this a **first order system** of ODEs because both equations are first order.  **Matrix form of the system**  Before we consider how the leak in tank 2 affects this system, let's rewrite the system in terms of vectors and matrices.  Reorder the terms on the right-hand side so that the variables [mathjaxinline]h_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]h_2[/mathjaxinline] appear in the same order in both equations, and use the shorter notation [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\dot{h}=\\frac{dh}{dt}[/mathjaxinline]:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\dot{h_1}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle - a h_1 + a h_2[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{h_2}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle a h_1- a h_2,[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Now, by matrix multiplication, the **vector equation** , or the **matrix form** of this system, is  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} \\dot{h_1}\\\\\\ \\dot{h_2}\\\\\\ \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} -a & a \\\\\\ a & -a\\\\\\ \\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix} h_1\\\\\\ h_2 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]| (2.4)   ---|---      This equation relates vector function [mathjaxinline]\\, \\begin{pmatrix} h_1\\\\\\ h_2 \\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline] with its first derivative [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\, \\begin{pmatrix} \\dot{h_1}\\\\\\ \\dot{h_2}\\\\\\ \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline]  Let us verify that this vector equation is equivalent to the original system by working out the matrix multiplication:  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} \\dot{h_1}\\\\\\ \\dot{h_2}\\\\\\ \\end{pmatrix} =\\begin{pmatrix} {\\color{orange}{-a}} & {\\color{orange}{a}} \\\\\\ {\\color{blue}{a}} & {\\color{blue}{-a}} \\\\\\ \\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix} h_1\\\\\\ h_2 \\end{pmatrix}=\\begin{pmatrix} ({\\color{orange}{-a}} ) h_1 + {\\color{orange}{a}} h_2 \\\\\\ {\\color{blue}{a}} h_1 +({\\color{blue}{- a}} ) h_2 \\\\\\ \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      We see that the first row gives the first DE of the original system, and the second row gives the second DE .  The [mathjaxinline]\\, 2 \\times 2 \\,[/mathjaxinline] matrix  [mathjax]\\begin{pmatrix} -a & a \\\\\\ a & -a\\\\\\ \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      in the equation above is known as the **coefficient matrix** of the system. This matrix encodes all information of the system.    Biological medicines in large storage tanks", "filename": "12_motivationforsystems-tab6-text1.html", "title": "Biological medicines in large storage tanks"}

{"pageid": 130, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@13_homogeneous2by2linearsystems-tab4", "text": "### Solving 2 by 2 homogeneous linear systems of ODEs  Recall that we are looking for basic solutions of the form    |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\mathbf v\\, e^{\\lambda t}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{where } \\mathbf v=\\begin{pmatrix} a_1\\\\\\ a_2\\end{pmatrix}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.62)   ---|---|---|---|---       **Question 4.1** For which pairs [mathjaxinline](\\lambda ,\\mathbf v),[/mathjaxinline] consisting of a scalar and a nonzero vector, is the vector-valued function [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}= \\mathbf v\\, e^{\\lambda t} \\,[/mathjaxinline] a solution to the system [mathjaxinline]\\dot{\\mathbf{x}}= \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline]?  **Solution:** Plug [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}= \\mathbf v\\, e^{\\lambda t} \\,[/mathjaxinline] into the system:  |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda \\mathbf ve^{\\lambda t}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf ve^{\\lambda t} \\qquad \\textrm{(for all } t).[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Cancelling [mathjaxinline]\\, e^{\\lambda t} \\,[/mathjaxinline] on the two sides, we get  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda \\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf v.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      **Conclusion:** [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf ve^{\\lambda t}[/mathjaxinline] is a solution to the system of differential equations if and only if the system of **algebraic** equations [mathjaxinline]\\lambda \\mathbf v= \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf v\\,[/mathjaxinline] is satisfied.    Let us see what the algebraic equations in [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda \\mathbf v= \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf v\\,[/mathjaxinline] are for a specific matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline]. Consider the system  |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}\\qquad \\text{where }\\, \\mathbf{A}=\\begin{pmatrix} -1& 3\\\\\\ 2& 1\\end{pmatrix},\\,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.63)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---      The vector function [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}\\, =\\, \\mathbf ve^{\\lambda t}[/mathjaxinline] is a solution if and only if the following algebraic system is satisfied:  |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda \\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.64)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longleftrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda \\begin{pmatrix} a_1\\\\\\ a_2\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} -1& 3\\\\\\ 2& 1\\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} a_1\\\\\\ a_2\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.65)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longleftrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda a_1[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle -1a_1+3a_2[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.66)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lambda a_2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 2a_1+a_2.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.67)      This is a system of 2 algebraic equations with 3 unknowns, [mathjaxinline]\\lambda \\,[/mathjaxinline] [mathjaxinline]\\, a_1\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, a_2.[/mathjaxinline] Moreover, the equations are not linear because of the products [mathjaxinline]\\lambda a_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda a_2[/mathjaxinline]. In many situations, 2 nonlinear algebraic equations in 3 unknowns cannot be solved.    But here, we can make progress by splitting the problem into two parts. First, we view [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline] not as an unknown but as a parameter. If [mathjaxinline]\\lambda[/mathjaxinline] is fixed, then we obtain a linear homogeneous [mathjaxinline]\\, 2\\times 2[/mathjaxinline] system of algebraic equations for the unknowns [mathjaxinline]a_1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]a_2[/mathjaxinline], which we can write in the form  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(-1-\\lambda \\right) a_1+3a_2[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 2a_1+\\left(1-\\lambda \\right)a_2[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{or in matrix form}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} -1-\\lambda & 3\\\\\\ 2& 1-\\lambda \\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} a_1\\\\\\ a_2\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      **Vector and matrix notation**  Let  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}=\\begin{pmatrix} -1& 3\\\\\\ 2& 1\\end{pmatrix}\\qquad \\mathbf v=\\begin{pmatrix} a_1\\\\\\ a_2\\end{pmatrix}\\qquad \\mathbf{0}=\\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix},[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.68)   ---|---|---|---      then [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf ve^{\\lambda t}[/mathjaxinline] is a solution to the system of DEs [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}= \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}\\,[/mathjaxinline] if and only if the following homogeneous linear algebraic system is satisfied:  |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} -1-\\lambda & 3\\\\\\ 2& 1-\\lambda \\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} a_1\\\\\\ a_2\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ 0\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---      We write  | \\begin{pmatrix} -1& 3\\\\\\ 2& 1\\end{pmatrix}-\\lambda \\begin{pmatrix} 1& 0\\\\\\ 0& 1\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.69)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Therefore, a more compact way to write this is:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle ( \\mathbf{A}-\\lambda \\mathbf{I}) \\mathbf v[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{0}\\qquad \\text{where }\\, \\mathbf{I}\\, =\\, \\begin{pmatrix} 1& 0\\\\\\ 0& 1\\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.70)   ---|---|---|---|---|---       **The general case:**    In general, for constant matrix [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}=\\mathbf ve^{\\lambda t}[/mathjaxinline] solves [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline] if and only if [mathjaxinline](\\mathbf{A}-\\lambda \\mathbf{I})\\mathbf v=\\mathbf{0}[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 131, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@ourcourse/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@ourcourse-tab5", "text": "There are 5 categories of graded problems in 18.032x: Lecture exercises, Recitation problems, Part A Homework, Part B Homework, and the Final Exam. All content and problems are open to audit learners, **except** for the final exam.    * **Lecture exercises** These are the problems that are interspersed through the lecture content. These problems count for 10% of your grade.   These problems will be used to motivate theory, practice concepts, and review material from previous lectures. You are graded on these problems. This is where you will do the majority of your learning. We encourage you to make mistakes and learn from them!    * **Recitation problems** There is a recitation worksheet associated to each lecture. Most problems have an answer box that allows you to check your answers with up to 10 attempts. The entries of these answer boxes counts towards 10% of your grade.  At MIT, recitations are group work sessions led by a teaching assistant. We are hoping to create a similar collaborative learning environment on the forum. Recitations involve the type of problem solving we will be asking of you in the homework. You are free to discuss the solutions to these problems on the forum before the due date! In fact, we will not reveal detailed solutions to these problems, so to ensure that you have understood these problems, please take the opportunity to discuss and learn from each other. (Note that we will give simple answers to most questions so you can see the expected answer.)    * **Part A Homework** Each unit has 1 Part A Homework assignment, which gives you an opportunity to practice what you learned. These problems count for 10% of your total grade.   Wait until the end of the unit to attempt these problems. These problems help you identify the concepts that you have forgotten, and aid in long-term retention. These problems are mostly mechanical\u2013asking you to practice methods, and techniques learned in each unit. Each problem typically tests knowledge from only one section in a unit. (We won't necessarily tell you which one though!)    * **Part B Homework** Each unit has 1 Part B Homework assignment. The part B homework counts for 25% of your total grade.   The problems on this homework combine ideas from all of the sequences in the unit. These problems are mostly in the form of word problems which ask you to apply the methods learned to new scenarios.    * **Final** The final exam is the culmination of your learning, and will account for 45% of your grade. These problems cover all of the material in this course.   Grading", "filename": "ourcourse-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Grading"}

Solve the system   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(x,y)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle h(x,y)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  |      to find all the critical points in the [mathjaxinline](x,y)[/mathjaxinline]-phase plane. At each critical point [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline],   Compute the numerical [mathjaxinline]2 \\times 2[/mathjaxinline] matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}\\colon =\\mathbf{J}(a,b)[/mathjaxinline], by evaluating [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{J}(x,y)[/mathjaxinline] at [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline].  Determine whether the critical point is stable (attracting) or not:  [mathjax]\\textrm{stable} \\iff \\mathrm{tr}\\mathbf{A}< 0 \\, \\, \\textrm{ and }\\, \\, \\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}> 0.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Or, for a more detailed picture, find the eigenvalues of [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline] to classify the phase portrait for the \u201clinear approximation system\"  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} \\dot{X} \\\\\\ \\dot{Y} \\end{pmatrix} \\approx \\mathbf{A}\\begin{pmatrix} X \\\\\\ Y \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---      For further details: If the eigenvalues are real, find the eigenlines. {"pageid": 135, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@33_autonomoussystemsstability/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@33_autonomoussystemsstability-tab2", "text": "The basic model for two interacting populations is the [mathjaxinline]2\\times 2[/mathjaxinline] autonomous system of **Lotka-Volterra equations** :  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(ax-bx^2\\right) \\pm cxy[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.95)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(dy-hy^2\\right)\\pm fxy.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.96)      where the equations govern the rates of change of the populations [mathjaxinline]\\, x\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, y\\,[/mathjaxinline] respectively, and [mathjaxinline]a,\\, b,\\, c,\\, d,\\, f,\\, h\\,[/mathjaxinline] are the 6 parameters of the system. Note that here we have written the equations so that the parameters are positive.  In each equation, the two terms in the brackets model the **logistic** growth of a single population in the absence of the other.  **Interactions between the two populations**    The final term in each equation is proportional to the product [mathjaxinline]xy,\\,[/mathjaxinline] and models the effect of interaction between [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] on the respective population. For example, in the first equation, which governs the rate of change of the population [mathjaxinline]\\, x,\\,[/mathjaxinline] if the term proportional to [mathjaxinline]\\, xy\\,[/mathjaxinline] is positive, then [mathjaxinline]\\dot{x}\\,[/mathjaxinline] is increased. This means interactions are beneficial to the [mathjaxinline]\\, x\\,[/mathjaxinline] population.    The signs of the [mathjaxinline]xy[/mathjaxinline] terms in the two equations determine which of the following scenarios are modeled.    1.  **Competition** :   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(ax-bx^2\\right) -cxy[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.97)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(dy-hy^2\\right)-fxy.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.98)      If the terms proportional to [mathjaxinline]xy[/mathjaxinline] in both equations are negative, then interactions decrease the rates of change of both [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]. This models two species mutually harmful to one another. An example is moose and deer competing for vegetation in the same habitat.    2. **Mutualism** :   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(ax-bx^2\\right) +cxy[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.99)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(dy-hy^2\\right)+fxy.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.100)      If the [mathjaxinline]xy[/mathjaxinline] terms in both equations are positive, then interactions increase the rates of change of both [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]. This models two species mutually beneficial to one another. An example is human and the bacteria living in our digestive system.    3. **Predator-prey** :   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(ax-bx^2\\right) -cxy[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.101)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left(dy-hy^2\\right)+fxy.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.102)      If the signs of the [mathjaxinline]xy[/mathjaxinline] terms in the two equations are different, then interaction benefits one population but harms the other. This models a predator species and a prey species. An example is wolves and deer, with the deer being a food source for the wolves.  In this lecture, we will sketch the full phase portraits of two predator-prey systems and discuss the structural stability of these along the way.  Introduction", "filename": "33_autonomoussystemsstability-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Introduction"}

{"pageid": 139, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@15_stability/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@15_stability-tab4", "text": "The quadratic formula gives  [mathjax]\\lambda _{1,2}=\\frac{\\mathrm{tr}\\mathbf{A}}{2}\\pm \\sqrt{\\frac{(\\mathrm{tr}\\mathbf{A})^2}{4}-\\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Therefore, the eigenvalues [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda _{1},\\, \\lambda _2\\,[/mathjaxinline] are  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{real}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{if} \\, \\, \\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}\\leq \\frac{(\\mathrm{tr}\\mathbf{A})^2}{4},[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.75)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{non-real}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{if}\\, \\, \\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}>\\frac{(\\mathrm{tr}\\mathbf{A})^2}{4}.[/mathjaxinline] | | (3.76)       **Critical parabola**    The real roots are distinct when the strict inequality [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}<\\frac{(\\mathrm{tr}\\mathbf{A})^2}{4}\\,[/mathjaxinline] holds, and repeated when  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\, \\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}=\\frac{(\\mathrm{tr}\\mathbf{A})^2}{4}.[/mathjaxinline] | | (3.77)   ---|---|---|---      This defines the **critical parabola** , which divides the [mathjaxinline]\\, (\\text{Tr},\\text{Det})[/mathjaxinline]-plane into two regions representing systems with different types of behavior.  ![The horizontal axis is the trace Tr, the vertical axis is the determinant Det, and the critical parabola is given by the equation Det equals Tr squared over 4](/static/images/u3s4_tdplanepara.svg)  Critical parabola continued", "filename": "15_stability-tab4-text2.html", "title": "Critical parabola continued"}

{"pageid": 141, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@15_stability/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@15_stability-tab5", "text": "Consider the [mathjaxinline]\\, 2\\times 2\\,[/mathjaxinline] system [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline]. **Suppose that** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}< \\frac{\\left(\\mathrm{tr}\\mathbf{A}\\right)^2}{4}}}[/mathjaxinline] **.**  Then the eigenvalues are **real and distinct** .    * If [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}<0[/mathjaxinline], then the product [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _1 \\lambda _2 < 0[/mathjaxinline], so the eigenvalues have opposite sign: saddle.     * If [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}>0[/mathjaxinline], then the eigenvalues have the same sign, and       * if [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{tr}\\mathbf{A}> 0[/mathjaxinline]: nodal source,       * if [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{tr}\\mathbf{A}< 0[/mathjaxinline]: nodal sink.   ![Trace determinant plane. Regions below critical parabola and above the horizontal Tr axis are nodes. Nodes to the left of the vertical Det axis are nodal sinks, nodes to the right of the vertical Det axis are nodal sources. Region below the critical parabola but also below the horizontal Tr axis are saddles.](/static/images/u3s4_tdnodesaddleanswer.svg)  Distinct real eigenvalues", "filename": "15_stability-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Distinct real eigenvalues"}

{"pageid": 143, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@15_stability/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@15_stability-tab4", "text": "Let us re-express the classification of phase portraits of a [mathjaxinline]2\\times 2\\,[/mathjaxinline] system [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}\\,[/mathjaxinline] in terms of [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{tr}\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline].  Recall that the types of phase portraits that we discussed in the last lecture are determined by the eigenvalues [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _1,\\lambda _2[/mathjaxinline] of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline].    * **Nodes** : if [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _{1,2}\\,[/mathjaxinline] are real and distinct, and of the same sign.     * **Saddles** : if [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _{1,2}\\,[/mathjaxinline] are real and distinct, and of opposite sign.     * **Centers** : if [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _{1,2}\\,[/mathjaxinline] are purely imaginary [mathjaxinline]\\, \\pm bi\\,[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]\\, b\\neq 0\\,[/mathjaxinline].     * **Spirals** : if [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _{1,2}\\,[/mathjaxinline] are complex with nonzero real and nonzero imaginary parts [mathjaxinline]\\, a\\pm bi\\,[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]a\\neq 0\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, b\\neq 0[/mathjaxinline].   The eigenvalues [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda _{1},\\, \\lambda _2\\,[/mathjaxinline] are the roots of the characteristic polynomial, which can be written in terms of the trace and determinant of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]\\mathrm{det}( \\mathbf{A}-\\lambda \\mathbf{I}) = ({\\color{blue}{\\lambda }} - \\lambda _1)({\\color{blue}{\\lambda }} - \\lambda _2)= {\\color{blue}{\\lambda }} ^2 - (\\mathrm{tr}\\mathbf{A}) {\\color{blue}{\\lambda }} + (\\mathrm{det}\\mathbf{A}).[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Critical parabola", "filename": "15_stability-tab4-text1.html", "title": "Critical parabola"}

{"pageid": 145, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@31_pendulums/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@31_pendulums-tab1", "text": "### Objectives  After this section and some practice, you should be able to:    * Model the **non-linear** pendulum.     * **Linearize** a **non-linear autonomous system** near **critical points** .     * Use the **Jacobian matrix** to find the linearization of a system near a critical point.     * Determine the **stability** of critical points.     * **Sketch trajectories** of non-linear autonomous systems near stable critical points. {"pageid": 146, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@14_phaseportraits/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@14_phaseportraits-tab5", "text": "The [mathjaxinline]\\, (x,y)[/mathjaxinline]-plane on which we sketch the trajectories of solutions is known as the **phase plane** . The terminology comes from the fact that for companion systems, the [mathjaxinline](x,y)[/mathjaxinline]-plane is the [mathjaxinline](x,\\dot{x})[/mathjaxinline]-plane, which is known as the phase plane in physics.    A **phase portrait** of a system of DEs is a diagram consisting of the trajectories of **all** solutions to the system in the phase plane.    Suppose that the eigenvalues [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _1,\\lambda _2[/mathjaxinline] are **real and distinct, and have the same sign** .  Let [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_1[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf v_2[/mathjaxinline] be corresponding eigenvectors.    Since, [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda _1\\neq \\lambda _2,\\,[/mathjaxinline] the general solution is:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle c_1 \\mathbf v_1 e^{\\lambda _1 t} + c_2 \\mathbf v_2 e^{\\lambda _2 t}\\qquad (\\lambda _1\\neq \\lambda _2 \\, \\text{real}).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.16)   ---|---|---|---      Because [mathjaxinline]\\, \\lambda _1,\\, \\lambda _2\\,[/mathjaxinline] have the same sign, there are 2 types of phase portraits, corresponding to whether the eigenvalues are both negative or both positive. The behavior of these phase portraits will depend on which eigenvalue is bigger.          1. **Sink node** (or **Nodal sink** or **Attracting node** ): Eigenvalues are **both negative,** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\lambda _1,\\lambda _2<0}}[/mathjaxinline].    All nonzero trajectories flow from infinity **towards** [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{(0,0)}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline]  Trajectories not contained in the eigenlines become:      * parallel to the **(black) eigenline** corresponding to the **smaller (more negative) eigenvalue far from** [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{ (0,0)}[/mathjaxinline],       * tangent to the **(blue) eigenline** corresponding to the **larger (less negative) eigenvalue near** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{(0,0)}}[/mathjaxinline].   **Example of a solution:** [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}= e^{-2t} \\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix} + e^{-5t} \\begin{pmatrix} -1 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline].  | ![ ](/static/images/u3s3_nodesink.svg)   ---|---     2. **Source node** (or **Nodal source** or **Repelling node** ): Eigenvalues are **both positive, [mathjaxinline]\\lambda _1,\\lambda _2 >0[/mathjaxinline]** .    All nonzero trajectories flow from [mathjaxinline](0,0)[/mathjaxinline] **towards infinity**. Trajectories not contained in the eigenlines become:      * tangent to the **(blue) eigenline** corresponding to the **smaller eigenvalue near** [mathjaxinline]{\\color{blue}{\\mathbf{(0,0)}}}[/mathjaxinline].       * parallel to the **(black) eigenline** corresponding to the **larger eigenvalue far from** [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{(0,0)}[/mathjaxinline].   **Example of a solution:** [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}= e^{2t} \\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix} + e^{5t} \\begin{pmatrix} -1 \\\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline]  | ![ ](/static/images/u3s3_nodesource.svg)   ---|---    Phase portraits: distinct real eigenvalues: Nodes", "filename": "14_phaseportraits-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Phase portraits: distinct real eigenvalues: Nodes"}

{"pageid": 147, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@ourcourse/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@ourcourse-tab2", "text": "Differential equations are the language of the models we use to describe the world around us. Most phenomena require not a single differential equation, but a system of coupled differential equations. In this course, we will develop the mathematical toolset needed to understand 2x2 systems of first order linear and nonlinear differential equations. We will use 2x2 systems and matrices to model:    * predator-prey populations in an ecosystem,     * competition for tourism between two states,     * the temperature profile of a soft boiling egg,     * automobile suspensions for a smooth ride,     * pendulums, and     * RLC circuits that tune to specific frequencies.   Course Description", "filename": "ourcourse-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Course Description"}

{"pageid": 149, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@recitation16/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@recitation16-tab2", "text": "**Conditions for clockwise spirals**  Let [mathjaxinline]\\, \\mathbf{A}=\\begin{pmatrix} a& b\\\\\\ c& d\\end{pmatrix}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline]  What are the conditions that [mathjaxinline]a,\\, b,\\, c,\\, d\\,[/mathjaxinline] have to satisfy so that the system [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline] is a clockwise spiral? {"pageid": 150, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@12_motivationforsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@12_motivationforsystems-tab2", "text": "### More real life examples  Any time one rate of change is coupled with another, we have a system of differential equations. Here are some examples.    * **Physics:** To send the Juno spacecraft to Jupiter, NASA scientists needed to understand the full system of gravitational attraction among the planets, and its effect on the velocity and acceleration of Juno. This gives rise to a system of differential equations.     * **Electrical systems:** We have seen that an RLC circuit can be described by a single second order ODE. More complex circuits present in all electrical devices, such as computers and cell phones, are described by systems of differential equations.     * **Chemical reactions:** The time derivative of the concentration of a chemical species is a function of the reaction rates and concentrations of other species. These relations give systems of DEs.     * **Engineering:** Controlling robots, airplanes, and cars all require systems of differential equations.     * **Computer graphics:** Life-like animations of fire, smoke, water, snow, and moving cloth in movies all require simulating systems of DEs.     * **Gene expression network:** The time derivatives of mRNA and protein concentrations are functions of their degradation rates and transcription factors of the proteins. These relations constitute systems of DEs.     * **Network dynamics:** How a virus spreads in a population, the flow of traffic, and information flow in a social network can all be described by systems of DEs.   Real life examples", "filename": "12_motivationforsystems-tab2-text2.html", "title": "Real life examples"}

{"pageid": 151, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@12_motivationforsystems/block-v1:MITx+18.032x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@12_motivationforsystems-tab9", "text": "**Definition 9.1** A [mathjaxinline]\\, 2 \\times 2 \\,[/mathjaxinline] **first order linear** system of ODEs is one that can written in the form  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} \\dot{x}\\\\\\ \\dot{y} \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} a& b\\\\\\ c& d \\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix} x\\\\\\ y \\end{pmatrix}+\\begin{pmatrix} r_1\\\\\\ r_2 \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.28)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      or more compactly,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}+\\mathbf{r}\\qquad[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text{with}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} x\\\\\\ y \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.29)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  |  |  |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{A}(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} a& b\\\\\\ c& d \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.30)   |  |  |  |  |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\mathbf{r}(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{pmatrix} r_1\\\\\\ r_2 \\end{pmatrix}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.31)      Here, [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] is the independent variable; [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}[/mathjaxinline] is the vector of the dependent variables [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{x}=\\mathbf{x}(t)=\\begin{pmatrix} x(t)\\\\\\ y(t)\\end{pmatrix}.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Similarly, the coefficient matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}(t)[/mathjaxinline] and the vector [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{r}(t)[/mathjaxinline] may depend on [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] but not on any of the dependent variables. For example, [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}(t)[/mathjaxinline] can be [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} \\cos t & \\sin t\\\\\\ -\\sin (t)& \\cos t \\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{r}(t)[/mathjaxinline] can be [mathjaxinline]\\begin{pmatrix} e^t \\\\\\ t\\end{pmatrix}[/mathjaxinline].    The system is called **first order** because the highest derivatives involved are first derivatives.    The system is called **homogeneous** if [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{r}(t)[/mathjaxinline] equals the zero vector, and **inhomogeneous** if [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{r}(t)[/mathjaxinline] is nonzero.  **Comparison with single ODEs:** The definitions of linearity and homogeneity for systems are analogous to those for single ODEs. Recall that a single first order linear ODE is one that can be written in the standard form  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}+p(t)x \\, =\\, q(t) \\quad[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}\\, =\\, -p(t)x + q(t)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.32)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      which is the same as  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\dot{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle a(t)x + r(t) \\qquad \\text{with }\\, a=-p, \\, r=q[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.33)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Here [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] is the independent variable, [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] is the dependent variable, and the functions [mathjaxinline]p(t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]q(t)[/mathjaxinline] depend only on [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] and not [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]. The DE is homogeneous if [mathjaxinline]q(t)=0[/mathjaxinline] and inhomogeneous if [mathjaxinline]q(t)\\neq 0[/mathjaxinline].  **Time dependent linear model for soft boiling an egg**    In fact, we can build a more sophisticated, but still linear, model of soft boiling an egg. As the egg cooks, the heat transfer properties between the egg yolk and egg white, and between the egg white and the water bath may change. Therefore, the conductivity coefficients [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] are functions of time. This means the coefficient matrix [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{A}[/mathjaxinline], whose entries are combinations of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline], is also a function of time. Similarly, the temperature [mathjaxinline]T_e[/mathjaxinline] of the water bath may change as time passes, so [mathjaxinline]T_e[/mathjaxinline] and therefore the vector [mathjaxinline]\\mathbf{r}=\\begin{pmatrix} 0\\\\\\ bT_e \\end{pmatrix}\\,[/mathjaxinline] are also functions of time. The system of DE with these time-dependent parameters changes remains linear, since it can be put into the form [mathjaxinline]\\, \\dot{\\mathbf{x}}=\\mathbf{A}(t) \\mathbf{x}+\\mathbf{r}(t)[/mathjaxinline].  Order, linearity and homogeneity", "filename": "12_motivationforsystems-tab9-text1.html", "title": "Order, linearity and homogeneity"}

It corresponds to a **constant solution** to the system. Geometrically, a critical point is a trajectory that stays at the same point on the phase plane. For this reason, a critical point is also called a **stationary point** or a **fixed point** . We often need to use physical intuition to narrow our search for them.  **Remark 6.2** We have stated earlier that trajectories never cross. While it is true that no two trajectories can have a point in common, it **is** possible for two trajectories to have the same limit as [mathjaxinline]t \\to +\\infty[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]t \\to -\\infty[/mathjaxinline], so they can **appear** to touch.
